[Event "Tournament"]
[Date "2020.03.19"]
[Round "3.1"]
[White "Ding, Liren"]
[Black "Caruana, Fabiano"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D17"]
[Opening "Slav Defense: Czech Variation, Wiesbaden Variation"]
[StudyName "The Candidates Tournament 2020 - Round 3"]
[ChapterName "Ding, Liren - Caruana, Fabiano"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/58yy3Hhw/s9irFYRy"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/lovlas"]

{ Today we are taking a look at the intense game between Fabiano Caruana and Ding Liren. Before we start I just want to say that if there ever was a time to declare that a game is above your level, this is the time for me. This game makes no sense at all. So please put on your safety googles and engine hat and enjoy the ride. }
1. d4 { [%clk 1:40:56] } 1... d5 { [%clk 1:41:24] } 2. c4 { [%clk 1:41:20] } 2... c6 { This is known as the Slav Defence. } { [%clk 1:41:21] } 3. Nf3 { [%clk 1:40:46] } 3... Nf6 { [%clk 1:41:39] } 4. Nc3 { [%clk 1:39:58] } 4... dxc4 { Has been a solid choice for black for a long time. The plan is simply to grab a pawn and develop your pieces while white spends time winning the pawn back. } { [%clk 1:40:30] } 5. a4 { [%clk 1:40:24] } (5. e4 { Moves like this allows black to keep his pawn with } 5... b5 { The question in these lines is wether white can get enough play in the centre to compensate for a pawn. In my experience the answer is generally that he can. }) 5... Bf5 { This is known as the Czech variation of the Slav and has been the main line for as long as I can remember. } { [%clk 1:40:42] } 6. Ne5 { [%clk 1:40:37] } 6... e6 { [%clk 1:40:42] } (6... Nbd7 7. Nxc4 Qc7 (7... Nb6 8. Ne5 a5 { Is another way to play this line as black } (8... Nbd7 9. Nc4 (9. Qb3 { If white doesn't want a quick draw he can play this strong move and win instead. } { Kasparov, Garry - Timman, Jan H, 1-0, Riga Tal Memorial, 1995, https://lichess.org/IFKWmZeQ }) 9... Nb6 { Would be a way to circumvent the Sophia rules if you are looking for a quick draw. })) 8. g3 e5 { Was all the fuzz when I was young and promising and still remain one of the main lines. } 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Bf4 Nfd7 { and so on }) 7. f3 { [%clk 1:40:16] } 7... Bb4 { This is all standard and well known stuff. } { [%clk 1:40:40] } 8. Nxc4 { [%clk 1:32:56] } (8. e4 { Leads to very sharp complications after } 8... Bxe4 9. fxe4 Nxe4 10. Bd2 Qxd4 { Three pawns for a piece. The white king is also gonna have some problems finding a safe hiding spot. } 11. Nxe4 Qxe4+ 12. Qe2 Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Qd5+ 14. Kc3 (14. Kc2 { Kramnik, Vladimir - Shirov, Alexei, 1-0, Linares 17th, 2000, https://lichess.org/xewoMCnz }) 14... O-O 15. Qe3 b5 16. Be2 Nd7 17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. Rhd1 Qe7 19. Kc2 a5 20. Bf3 Rac8 21. Qe5 g6 22. axb5 cxb5 23. Qxb5 Rc5 24. Qd7 Qg5 25. Qd4 Rfc8 26. Ra3 Rb5 27. Rd2 Rb4 28. Kd1 Rcb8 29. Ke2 Qb5 30. Ke1 Rxb2 31. Rxb2 Qxb2 32. Qxb2 Rxb2 33. Rxa5 c3 34. Rc5 Rb1+ 35. Ke2 Rc1 36. Kd3 Kg7 37. Rxc3 Rxc3+ 38. Kxc3 f5 39. Kd4 Kf6 40. Bd1 h5 41. Bf3 h4 42. Be2 g5 43. Ba6 g4 44. Bb7 e5+ 45. Kd5 f4 46. Ke4 { Bacrot, Etienne - Anand, Viswanathan, 1-0, Nanjing Pearl Spring 3rd, 2010, https://lichess.org/1bWU3DNb }) 8... O-O { [%clk 1:40:08] } 9. Kf2!? { This weird looking move finally prepares to push e4. Eventually white can try to castle manually by bringing his bishop and rook out. } { [%clk 1:33:21] } (9. Bg5 { Looks more natural. But is probably less critical. } 9... h6 10. Bh4 c5 11. dxc5 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 { Beliavsky, Alexander G - Portisch, Lajos, 1/2-1/2, Hoogovens, 1985, https://lichess.org/5HQhLQKf } (12. Kxd1 { Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar - Solak, Dragan, 1/2-1/2, Dresden ol (Men) 38th, 2008, https://lichess.org/RDWZjypf })) (9. e4 { Doesn't really work because of } 9... Nxe4 10. fxe4 Qh4+ 11. Kd2 Qxe4 $13 { White's king is in trouble } 12. Qf3 Qxd4+ { Matveeva, Svetlana - Kosteniuk, Alexandra, 0-1, RUS-ch (Women), 2005, https://lichess.org/R3yZeiNO }) 9... e5!? $146 { This is where the funky business begins. As far as I am aware this is novelty, and a very interesting one. White seemingly just gives away a pawn for nothing. But Caruana is generally very well prepared and this is obviously something straight out of his opening lab.
Black tries to take advantage of the weak white king on f2 by blowing up the dark squares. My engine hates it, but I have more faith in Caruana's preparation than my lousy annoying engine.
Some may argue that the move is more dubious than interesting, but as the game will show Caruana had chances to equalize. } { [%clk 1:40:28] } (9... Bg6 10. e4 c5 { Transposes to the 9...c5 line. }) (9... c5 { Has been tried 40 times in the lichess master db. But it doesn't really seem to solve all of blacks problem. Mainly that his pieces on the kingside are a bit stuck after e4.
The white king on f2 isn't really a problem since it's hard to bring it under attack. } 10. e4 Bg6 11. Na2 { Iturrizaga, E. - Shankland, S., 1-0, PRO League Group Stage, 2019, https://lichess.org/VtWYLE9x } { White scores very well in this line. He has managed to play e4 and is ready to finish development. Meanwhile the black pieces on the kingside are looking into a brick wall. Probably white is better. }) 10. Nxe5 { Taking the pawn must be the critical test } { [%clk 1:16:44] } (10. dxe5 { Is probably another test of 9...e5. But taking with the knight simply seems more natural. }) 10... Bc2! { Without this move e5 probably doesn't make much sense. Bc2 forces white to place his pieces clumsily. } { [%clk 1:40:35] } 11. Qd2 { This isn't really a move you want to play. Self-pinning the knight on c3, and blocking the c1 bishop. But there isn't really another option since Qxc2 just leads to equality. } { [%clk 1:09:32] } (11. Qxc2 Qxd4+ 12. e3 Qxe5 $10 { Must be fine for black. Material is even and black has easy development.
Maybe white can pretend to be slightly better with his bishop pair. But the black knights has a ton of room to play around with. }) 11... c5! { Another move designed to punish the white kings placement on f2. Forcing open the dark diagonals. } { [%clk 1:40:43] } 12. d5 { [%clk 0:53:25] } (12. e3 { Is probably the move I would have played if I was playing white. It just looks much safer and more solid than 12.d5. But it's probably not as good. }) 12... Bb3 { Is the logical move. Getting the bishop out of harms way. And making sure it won't get stuck } { [%csl Gd5] [%clk 1:40:44] } (12... Be4 { The silly engine wants to go here. It regains the d5-pawn since white cannot take on e4. But white is left with a strong bishop pair and central control. Probably not sufficient to equalize. } 13. fxe4?? (13. Qd1 Bxd5 (13... Bxc3 14. bxc3 Bxd5 15. e4 Be6 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Be2 $16 { Again white must be better due to his bishop pair and control over the center. }) 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Qxd5 Nxd5 16. e4 $16 { Is just much better for white due to his central dominance and bishop pair. Also the black bishop on a5 is a bit silly. }) 13... Nxe4+ $19) (12... Bg6 { From here it doesn't put pressure on the centre and can easily run out of room in the future if white gets to play e4. But e4 at once won't work as black can simply take it: } 13. e4?? Bxe4) 13. e4 { The only possible move that protects the d5-pawn and therefore the only natural move. } { [%clk 0:53:39] } 13... Re8 { [%clk 1:41:09] } 14. Qf4 { Another only move. White needs to protect all his pieces without falling for tricks. Not easy when your opponent is blitzing and obviously prepared this for centuries at home with his centurions. } { [%clk 0:41:34] } (14. Nd3? { Looks natural but fails due to the strong } 14... Rxe4!! { white's pieces are overloaded. } 15. fxe4 Nxe4+ 16. Nxe4 Bxd2 $19) 14... c4 { Caruana sacrifices another(!) pawn. It's not every day you can give two pawns out of the openings and still pretend to be fine.
In return black opens the diagonal against the white king and hopes that it will provide him with enough play.
It's worth noting that Caruana is still blitzing out his moves, so he is no doubt still well within his home preparation } { [%clk 1:40:59] } 15. Nxc4 { Ding gladly accepts the pawn in the most accurate way. } { [%clk 0:39:49] } (15. Bxc4? Bd6 16. Bxb3?? (16. Qe3 Nbd7 17. Bxb3 (17. Nxd7 Nxd7 18. Qe2 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 Rc8 { Even though black is two pawns down his dominance over the black squares leaves him a lot of compensation. }) 17... Bc5 { Would be a problem } { [%cal Gc5f2] }) 16... Qb6+ { Would be less than ideal. Black wins material. } 17. Be3 Qxb3 18. Bd4 Nbd7 $19 { [%csl Ge5] }) (15. Be3 { A simple developing moves fails to a very powerful pin } 15... Bd6 16. Bd4 Bxe5 { Is the most accurate way to punish white } (16... Nbd7 { Should also win material } 17. Nxf7 Bxf4 18. Nxd8 Rexd8 $19) 17. Bxe5 Nh5 18. Qf5 g6 { And black wins material since the bishop on e5 is gonna hang. }) 15... Nbd7 { [%clk 1:41:21] } 16. Be3 { [%clk 0:34:06] } 16... Nf8 { [%clk 1:41:12] } 17. Bd4 { Simple chess. White is improving the placement of his bishop and finds the ideal square for it, from which it controls almost half the board.
And he is still two pawns and black has to prove concretly that he has something for them.
If Caruana wasn't still blitzing out moves I would think white is just winning here. But Caruana is obviously still booked up. } { [%clk 0:25:52] } 17... Ng6 { [%clk 1:40:41] } (17... Rc8! 18. Ne3 Ng6 { Is probably a more accurate version for black. The knight on e3 disallows Qc1 and forces white to move his queen to a more exposed location. } 19. Qf5 (19. Qg3 { Runs into a nice tactic we have seen many times by now } 19... Bxc3 20. bxc3 Rxe4! { It's gonna be hard for white to solve both his issues with the king and defend the pawn on d5 at the same time. Black can also plan to sacrifice an exchange against the strong d4 bishop and get active play. Meanwhile white will struggle to bring out all his pieces. } 21. Kg1 Rxd4 22. cxd4 Nxd5 $13 { As long as the rook is stuck on h1 and the white king on g1 is exposed along the dark diagonals this position is very unclear. }) 19... Bc5 { The strong bishop on d4 has to go. } 20. Bxc5 Rxc5 21. Ra3 { Is an interesting line. Trying to take advantage of the fact that the bishop on b3 has no squares. } 21... Qb6 (21... Bc2!? { Miraculously the bishop finds a square. } 22. Nxc2 (22. g3 { Allows the white queen a safe square on g2. } 22... Qb6 { [%cal Gf1b5] } 23. Bb5 Re5 24. Qh3 Bxe4 25. fxe4 Rxc3 26. Rxc3 Nxe4+ 27. Kg2 Nxc3 28. Qc8+ Nf8 $13) 22... Re5 23. Qh3 (23. Qxe5 Nxe5 { White has a rook, a piece and two pawns for the queen. This combined with his space advantage and nice center might be sufficient. But with the white king exposed it's probably black that is playing for a win. }) 23... Nf4 24. Qg3 N6h5 25. Qg4?? (25. Rb3 { White can also sack his queen like this. There is just too many different queen sacks to mention them all. And they all have different nuances. Personally I prefer to not sacrifice my queen, unless there is imminent mate. } 25... Nxg3 26. hxg3) 25... f5! 26. exf5 Qb6 { Leaves white in huge trouble. } { [%cal Gb6f2] }) 22. Bb5 Re5 23. a5 Qc7 24. Rxb3 Rxf5 25. Nxf5 $13) 18. Qf5 { [%clk 0:25:10] } (18. Qc1! { Was the move everyone screamed out in the broadcast chat and of course it's the engine move. The reason it's the best move is that Qe3 and Qd2 doesn't really work tactically and that the queen is less exposed on c1 than f5.
Nd2 is coming and the bishop on b3 is in trouble. } { [%csl Gb3] } 18... Bxc4 (18... Rc8 19. Nd2 { Black has to sacrifice material to hope to have any chances, but it cannot be enough. } 19... Nxe4+ (19... Bxd5 20. exd5 Nxd5 21. Nb3 $18 { A full piece up. After white finishes development there is nothing black can do. }) 20. fxe4 Bxd5 21. Qd1 $18 { White is a full piece up for some activity and a slightly weak king. But white just has to finish development and bring his King to g1 to be completely winning. } (21. exd5?? Qh4+ 22. g3 Qxd4+ 23. Kg2 Bc5 $19 { White is getting mated })) 19. Bxc4 Rc8 20. Bb5 { Just doesn't look like any fun for black. White is two full pawns up and is ready to bring his rook on h1 out and castle manually with Kg1 if he has to. }) (18. Qe3? { Doesn't work. } 18... Rc8 19. Nd2 Nxd5 20. Nxd5 Bxd5 { leaves black with plenty of compensation for one pawn. }) (18. Qd2? Nxe4+! 19. fxe4 Rxe4 20. Be2?? (20. g3 Bxc4 21. Bxc4 Rc8! { White is forced to give up material due to the threat of Rxd4 followed by Bc5. } 22. Be2 (22. Nxe4 Bxd2 23. Nxd2 Rxc4 24. Nxc4 Qxd5 $17) 22... Rxd4! 23. Qxd4 Bc5 $19) 20... Bxc4 21. Bxc4 Qh4+ { wins } 22. g3 Rxd4 $19) 18... Bxc4 { Until this move Caruana had been blitzing, This is the first time he thought for a few minutes. My guess is that he is still in book. Caruana is probably one of the best prepared players in the world and it would be unlike him to enter super complicated positions like this without deep knowledge.
Assuming the engine is correct that 17...Rc8 18.Ne3 Ng6 was a more accurate way to play it is possible that Caruana got his lines mixed up. } { [%clk 1:34:25] } 19. Bxc4 { [%clk 0:25:32] } 19... Qc7 { Another quickly played move by Caruana. } { [%clk 1:34:39] } 20. Be2 { [%clk 0:18:30] } 20... Bc5 { Black has to try to get rid of the monster bishop on d4 if he is ever gonna hope to get enough play on the dark squares to compensate for two full pawns. } { [%clk 1:32:45] } 21. Bxc5 { [%clk 0:16:21] } 21... Qxc5+ { [%clk 1:18:48] } (21... Re5 22. Qh3 Nf4 23. Qh4 g5 { Mysteriously leaves black with enough play for the two pawns according to Stockfish. Personally I don't believe it. A pawn is a pawn, and two pawns are two pawns. But, white will be left with his poor bishop on e2 and trouble to bring the h1-rook out. So maybe the engine has a point. It usually does. Stockfish isn't nicknamed "Dream Crusher" for no reason. } 24. Qxf4!? { The engine shows that white can safely gives up a full queen for a piece here. } (24. Qg3 { Is another way to give up the queen. } 24... N6h5 25. Bd4 (25. Qg4?? Qxc5+ $19) 25... Nxg3 26. hxg3 Nxe2 27. Nxe2 f5 $13 { I have absolutely no idea what's going on in this resulting endgame. But, the engine gives it as 0.00 so I guess it's equal. But it's massively unclear. White is getting a rook, a knight and two pawns for the queen. Both the kings are kinda exposed which would probably result in a interesting game. }) 24... gxf4 25. Bd4 { White has two pieces for a queen. Some quick maths shows that this generally isn't sufficient 9 > 6, but his strong centre and strong bishop on d4 leaves him with sufficient play. White can also chose if he wants to give up his strong bishop for the rook on e5. } 25... Rg5 (25... a6 26. Rhd1 { White is somehow better. His two pieces for the queen,strong pieces and a strong centre provide enough compensation for the white. It's also clear that black has no clear cut way to make any progress. }) 26. Bxf6 { Would leave white in trouble as black now can pick up the strong bishop. You really do not want to exchange the laser bishop for the poor knight on f6. } 26... Qb6+ { [%cal Gb6f2,Gb6f6] }) 22. Kf1 { [%clk 0:16:50] } 22... h6? { Was played almost instantly by Caruana. But, this allows white to fix his kingside and might have been the deciding mistake. This shows how tin the margins are at the highest level. A simple natural move like h6 can throw a perfect preparation away. } { [%clk 1:18:29] } (22... Re5 23. Qh3 Qb4 24. Rb1 Nf4 25. Qg3 N6h5 26. Qf2 f5 { Is the engine line and would according to stockfish leave black with enough compensation for the two sacrificed pawns.
If the rook on h1 was on the other side of the king he would probably be winning. But as it is white is finding it hard to finish development.
This shows that with absolute perfect play the position is probably fine for black. But it's hyper complex and easy to misstep. But it probably indicates that Caruana's 9...e5 idea works. But I can't say that for certain. }) 23. Rd1 { Ding probably should have gone for g3 at once. But he is in no rush. It's a very natural move. The advantage of playing Rd1 over g3 is that after a move like Qb4 or Qb6 white can defend the b2 pawn from d2 instead of b1, a much more active square. } { [%clk 0:15:22] } (23. g3 { Beginning to untangle the pieces on the kingside right away seems very logical. The idea is just to go Kg2 and bring the rook on h1 out.
The pawn on g3 also takes away most of the squares from the black knights.
It's possible Ding wanted to avoid having to defend the b2-pawn with a rook on b1. } { [%cal Gf1g2,Gh1e1] } 23... Qb4 24. Rb1 { Looks a bit passive. But white is two pawns up and only have to untangle his pieces to be completely winning. }) 23... Qb6 { [%clk 1:08:24] } 24. Rd2! { The point of 23.Rd1. The rook is much more comfortable on d2 than on b1. } { [%clk 0:14:53] } 24... Qe3 { [%clk 1:07:51] } 25. Rc2 { [%clk 0:15:09] } 25... a6 { [%clk 1:04:34] } 26. Qh3! { Ding carefully bring his queen back into the game via h3 and later g3. } { [%clk 0:12:50] } 26... b5 { [%clk 1:03:00] } 27. Qg3 { [%clk 0:13:01] } 27... b4 { [%clk 1:01:33] } 28. Nd1 { [%clk 0:11:43] } 28... Qb3 { [%clk 1:01:53] } 29. Rd2 { [%clk 0:10:54] } 29... Qxa4 { Caruana regains one pawn. But white's extra pawn on d6 is enough to decide the game. } { [%clk 0:58:42] } 30. Qf2 { [%clk 0:10:28] } 30... Qd7 { [%clk 0:46:45] } 31. g3 { [%clk 0:09:38] } (31. Qd4 { Followed by Ne3 Kf2 and g3 also looks comfortable. The position is probably just winning for white. He is a pawn up with perfect control over the center and a strong guarded passer on d6. }) 31... Qh3+ { [%clk 0:46:26] } 32. Kg1 { The position is just hopelessly lost for black.White is a strong pawn up and will simply improve and untangle his pieces. The guarded d5 passer will decide the game. } { [%clk 0:09:26] } 32... a5 { [%clk 0:45:22] } 33. Qd4 { The queen takes up a strong position on d4 from where it controls almost the entire board. } { [%clk 0:08:41] } 33... Nh5 { Caruana tries to create complications but it's probably just lost. Ding Liren illustrates pitch perfect technique and convincingly converts. } { [%clk 0:35:36] } 34. Nf2 { [%clk 0:08:38] } 34... Qd7 { [%clk 0:36:00] } 35. f4 { [%clk 0:08:32] } 35... Nhxf4 { Probably a good practical try. Caruana fights on by giving a piece for some activity. It might work against a lesser player, like me, but not against the full force of Ding Liren. } { [%clk 0:36:09] } 36. gxf4 { [%clk 0:09:02] } 36... Nxf4 { [%clk 0:36:30] } 37. Kf1! { Allows the rook on h1 to join the game through the g1 square, with devestating effect } { [%clk 0:07:35] } 37... Qd6 { [%clk 0:33:30] } 38. Rg1 { [%clk 0:07:40] } 38... f6 { [%clk 0:29:36] } 39. Bb5 { [%clk 0:07:16] } 39... Re7 { [%clk 0:22:55] } 40. b3 { [%clk 0:04:23] } 40... Rf8 { [%clk 0:19:32] } 41. Rc2 { [%clk 0:42:27] } 41... Ne6 { [%clk 1:05:21] } 42. Qe3 { [%clk 0:41:46] } 42... Ng5 { [%clk 1:05:12] } 43. h4 { [%clk 0:41:41] } 43... Nf7 { [%clk 1:05:30] } 44. Rc6 { [%clk 0:39:43] } 44... Qb8 { [%clk 1:04:21] } 45. Qc5 { [%clk 0:37:48] } 45... Qd8 { [%clk 0:58:36] } 46. Rxf6 { [%clk 0:35:52] } 46... Kh8 { [%clk 0:55:38] } 47. Rf5 { [%clk 0:35:27] } 47... Rc7 { [%clk 0:53:28] } 48. Bc6 { [%clk 0:35:49] } 48... a4 { Another good practical try by Caruana. Trying to create a passer. But it's too little too late. } { [%clk 0:53:37] } 49. bxa4 { [%clk 0:31:40] } 49... b3 { [%clk 0:54:00] } 50. Rg3 { [%clk 0:29:45] } 50... b2 { [%clk 0:50:16] } 51. Rb3 { [%clk 0:30:06] } 51... Nd6 { [%clk 0:50:21] } 52. Rxf8+ { [%clk 0:30:13] } 52... Qxf8 { [%clk 0:50:46] } 53. Rxb2 { [%clk 0:30:00] } 53... Qf4 { [%clk 0:51:03] } 54. Rb8+ { [%clk 0:24:48] } 54... Kh7 { [%clk 0:51:28] } 55. Qc2 { [%clk 0:25:02] } 55... Re7 { [%clk 0:44:56] } 56. e5+ { [%clk 0:24:35] } 56... Nf5 { [%clk 0:45:21] } 57. Qe4 { [%clk 0:15:17] } 57... Qc1+ { [%clk 0:44:25] } 58. Kg2 { [%clk 0:15:27] } 58... g6 { [%clk 0:44:48] } 59. Rb3 { Caruana resigned. A perfect game by Ding Liren who took advantage when Caruana failed to find the equalizing continuation out of the crazy opening. I must say I am very impressed with Ding Liren's play in this game. Faced with a ton of challenges he plays close to perfect, and essentially refutes Caruana's new ideas over the board.
The jury is still out on the verdict of the 9...e5 novelty. But from what I can tell it's playable with perfect play. But, it's probably not something you want to try yourself unless you enjoy spending hours memorizing lines only to forget all of it and quickly lose, like me. I'm so gonna try this and fail miserably. Can't wait.
See you tomorrow for Round 4 of the Candidates! } { [%clk 0:14:08] } 1-0


