1. d4 { [%clk 1:40:55] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 1:40:42] } 2. c4 { [%clk 1:41:20] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:41:21] } 3. Nc3 { [%clk 1:41:44] } 3... Bb4 { The Nimzo-Indian. One of the most popular options against 1.d4. } { [%clk 1:40:36] } 4. f3 { A wise man once said that you should never ever move the f-pawn. But there are certain times you can break this rule. This is one of those times: The f3-nimzo. This was a very popular choice a few years back before it fell out of fashion. But it looks like the f3-nimzo is back on the menu. } { [%clk 1:42:07] } 4... d5 { [%clk 1:39:56] } 5. a3 { [%clk 1:42:05] } 5... Be7 { [%clk 1:40:18] } (5... Bxc3+ { Has traditionally been the main move but Alekseenko has other plans. } 6. bxc3 c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 (7... exd5 8. e3 O-O 9. Bd3 { is in my limited experience very comfortable for white. White will aim to develop his pieces, castle kingside and break with e4. If successful black is gonna suffer. }) 8. dxc5 Qa5 { is very double edged } 9. e4 Nf6 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qb3 Na6 12. Nh3 Nd7 13. Bxa6 Qxa6 14. c4 Ne5 15. Rc1 Bd7 16. Qc3 f6 17. O-O Ba4 18. Nf4 Rfd8 19. Bd4 Ng6 20. Nxg6 hxg6 21. e5 f5 22. h4 Rd7 23. Rf2 Rad8 24. Rd2 Qc6 25. Kh2 Qc7 26. Qe3 Kf7 27. Kg3 Rh8 28. Qf4 Qd8 29. Rb1 Bc6 30. Rbb2 Qa5 31. Be3 Rxd2 32. Rxd2 Qxa3 33. Qd4 Rc8 34. Rd1 Qa5 35. Ra1 Qd8 36. Qxd8 Rxd8 37. Rxa7 Rd3 38. Bg5 Rd4 39. Be3 { Carlsen, Magnus - Morozevich, Alexander, 1/2-1/2, Moscow Tal Memorial 4th, 2009, https://lichess.org/7UJz62AX }) 6. e4 { This is generally the main idea in the f3-nimzo. With a pawn on f3 you can quickly play e4 and take control over the centre. Once you control the centre you control the game. } { [%clk 1:42:29] } 6... dxe4 { [%clk 1:40:18] } 7. fxe4 { [%clk 1:42:52] } (7. Nxe4? { Wouldn't make much sense. White has the space advantage so he shouldn't trade pieces. }) 7... c5 { Forces white to make a comitment in the centre } { [%clk 1:40:44] } 8. d5 { [%clk 1:43:14] } 8... exd5 { [%clk 1:39:57] } 9. exd5 { White has a guarded passed pawn on d5. Because of this white seems to already be much better positionally. But if black is able to guard it by putting a fat piece infront of it and play around it, he might get enough activity to compensate for this. } { [%clk 1:43:35] } (9. cxd5 { Might look tempting at first glace. But this is probably suboptimal as it allows black to blockade the pawn and put pressure along the half-open e-file. }) 9... O-O { [%clk 1:39:27] } 10. Be2 { [%clk 1:44:02] } 10... Re8 { [%clk 1:33:40] } 11. Nf3 { [%clk 1:42:27] } 11... Bg4 { [%clk 1:31:30] } 12. O-O { [%clk 1:42:48] } 12... Nbd7 { It's worth noting that the strong d-pawn is forcing black to move his knight to a suboptimal square. In a dream world the knight would go to c6 and then later try to get to d4. On d7 it doesn't have a clear purpose or future. } { [%clk 1:30:15] } 13. d6!? { Caruana is playing fast and confidently. Making use of his passer at once. It might seem risky as the pawn is no longer guarded by his fellow pawn on c4. But seemingly Caruana has prepared this at home and knows what he is doing. } { [%clk 1:36:41] } 13... Bf8 { [%clk 1:30:02] } 14. h3 { [%clk 1:36:39] } 14... Bh5 { [%clk 1:18:51] } 15. Nb5 { [%clk 1:36:41] } 15... Re6? { [%clk 0:43:11] } (15... Qb6) (15... Rb8 16. Bf4 a6 17. Nc3 Qb6 18. Qd2 Ne4 19. Nxe4 Rxe4 20. Rad1 Rbe8 { [%csl Gd6] }) 16. Bf4 { [%clk 1:30:22] } 16... a6?! { [%clk 0:38:23] } (16... Re4 17. Bh2 a6 18. Nc7 Rc8 19. Qc2 Ne5 20. Nd5 Bg6 21. Nxe5 Rxe5 22. Nxf6+ gxf6 23. Qd2) 17. Nc7 { [%clk 1:23:32] } 17... Re4 { [%clk 0:38:09] } 18. Bh2?! { [%clk 1:21:39] } (18. Qd2) 18... Rc8 { [%clk 0:26:11] } 19. g4 { [%clk 1:14:56] } 19... Bxg4 { black is forced to give up a piece for two pawns. some quick maths will tell us that this isn't sufficient. But at least this leaves the white king exposed. Maybe black can draw about launching an attack. } { [%clk 0:16:15] } (19... Bg6 { would give white all the tempi in the world as the rook on e4 is in trouble. } 20. Bd3 Re3 21. Bxg6 hxg6 22. Qd2 Re4 (22... Rb3 23. Rad1 Ne4 24. Qc2 Re3 25. Bf4 { picks up the rook }) 23. Rad1 { Black really has no useful moves as white dominates the entire board. Eventually black will be forced to give away material anyways. } 23... Rxc4 24. g5 Ne4 25. Qd3 Nb6 26. b3 { wins material }) 20. hxg4 { black got his third pawn for the piece. But generally a piece is much more valuable than three pawns in middle games. } { [%clk 1:15:09] } 20... Nxg4 { [%clk 0:16:38] } 21. Bd3 { [%clk 1:12:47] } 21... Nxh2 { [%clk 0:15:28] } 22. Bxe4 { [%clk 1:11:37] } 22... Nxf1 { [%clk 0:15:13] } 23. Qxf1 { [%clk 1:11:05] } 23... Bxd6?! { Inaccuracy. Nf6 was best. } { [%clk 0:13:24] } (23... Nf6 24. Bf5 Rb8 25. Rd1 Bxd6 26. Nd5 g6 27. Qd3 Bg3 28. Be4 Nxd5 29. Bxd5 Qf6 30. Qe2) 24. Nd5 { If we look at piece placements and activity it's clear that white must be much better. Black needs to get some activity if he is gonna hope to be fine.
Another problem, as we will see in the game, is black's pieces being locked far away from his own king. White is ready to launch a fullscale attack. Meanwhile Alekseenko will find it difficulty, if not impossible, to find enough defender.
At the same time white's king might look exposed. But if you can't bring your pieces into the attack it doesn't matter. Even with no pawns the white king finds itself surrounded by friendly faces. } { [%clk 1:10:58] } 24... g6 { [%clk 0:05:48] } 25. Qh3! { The queen is being a nuaicense pinning the knight and rook to make sure that black can't untangle in time. At the same time this improves the queen prepares a very simple but beautiful plan. } { [%cal Gh3c8] [%clk 1:07:20] } 25... Kg7 { [%clk 0:06:15] } (25... Rc6 { The engine wants to go like this to try to untangle the pieces. It also avoids a very beautiful blow as we will see in the comment to the next move } 26. Rd1 Ne5 27. Ne3 Nxf3+ 28. Qxf3 Rb6 29. Bd5 Qg5+ 30. Ng4 Bf4 31. Kf1 h5 32. Nf2) 26. Kh1! { This is simple chess at its best. White is simply putting all his pieces on the best possible squares. The knight wants to go to g5 to join the attack. But g5 is guarded by the black queen. Caruana simply puts his king out of harms way, to bring his rook to g1 and defend the g5 square. Beautiful simple chess. } { [%clk 1:06:57] } (26. Bf5!! { is the silly but very pretty engine line. Simply giving away a full bishop to force open the kingside. But it's a silly looking move, so it's very understandable that this wasn't played, especially since Caruanas follow up also is really strong. } 26... gxf5 27. Kf2! { The plan. Black just doesn't have enough time to survive the imminent attack. } 27... Ne5 (27... Nf8 { This is way above my level so I'm just gonna let the engine do it's thing } 28. Rg1+ Ng6 29. Ng5 Qh8 30. Qxf5 Qf8 31. Rh1 h6 32. Qh3 Qh8 33. Qd7 Qe8 34. Qxd6 Rc6 (34... hxg5 { isn't possible because of } 35. Qf6+ Kg8 36. Rh6 Qf8 37. Ne7+ Nxe7 (37... Qxe7 38. Rxg6+ fxg6 39. Qxe7) 38. Rh8#) 35. Qh2 $18 { round and round the queen goes and eventually the engine wins. } 35... Ne5) 28. Nxe5 Bxe5 29. Rg1+ Kh8 30. Rh1 Qg8 31. Ne7 Qg3+ 32. Qxg3 Bxg3+ $18 { Silly engine }) 26... Ne5 { black tries to play actively, but it's already too late. White will simple bring all his pieces into the attack until the black kingside crumbles. } { [%clk 0:05:32] } (26... Ra8? { Doing nothing is not an answer. } 27. Rg1 Rb8 28. Ng5! { [%cal Gh3h7,Gh3c3] } 28... h5 29. Nxf7 Kxf7 30. Bxg6+ Kf8 31. Rf1+ Kg7 32. Rf7+ Kxg6 33. Qf5+ Kh6 34. Rh7#) 27. Nh4! { [%clk 1:03:09] } 27... h5? { This weakens the g6-pawn. } { [%clk 0:03:41] } (27... Rc6 { The silicon monster shows that the only try for black is to play passively on the kingside, and try to keep everything as intact as possible. } 28. Rg1 b5) (27... Nxc4? { A pawn doesn't matter if you are getting mated. } 28. Nf5+ gxf5 29. Rg1+ Kf8 30. Qxh7 Ke8 31. Rg8+ Kd7 32. Rxd8+ { White has won material and will also deliver mate shortly. }) 28. Rg1 { [%clk 1:00:03] } 28... Bf8 { [%clk 0:00:32] } (28... Rc6 29. Nf5+ Kf8 30. Nh6 Bc7 31. Qxh5 Rb6 32. Qh2 Rxb2 33. Qf4 Qd7 34. Bg2 Nd3 35. Qxc7) 29. Nf4 { All of white's pieces are targetting the black king. There is no defence. } { [%clk 0:48:27] } 29... Ng4 { [%clk 0:00:57] } 30. Nxh5+ { [%clk 0:48:29] } (30. Rxg4 hxg4 31. Qxg4 { was another brutal option. There is no defence against the magnitude of threats. } { [%csl Gg6] }) 30... gxh5 { [%clk 0:01:12] } 31. Bf5 { [%clk 0:43:28] } 31... Be7 { [%clk 0:01:10] } 32. Bxg4 { [%clk 0:42:21] } 32... hxg4 { [%clk 0:01:04] } 33. Qxg4+ { [%clk 0:42:04] } 33... Bg5 { [%clk 0:01:31] } 34. Qh5 { Alekseenko resigned as he was losing material and getting mated. Caruana is looking like a strong candidate to win the candidates. A beautiful game from start to finish. } { [%clk 0:41:44] } 1-0


