1. e4 { [%clk 1:41:25] } 1... e5 { [%clk 1:40:55] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:41:19] } 2... Nc6 { [%clk 1:41:19] } 3. Bb5 { [%clk 1:41:44] } 3... a6 { This is the Spanish one of the most common openings in the chess universe. It somehow manages to be very easy to learn, yet impossible to master. This has made it a favorite among chess players at every level. } { [%clk 1:41:44] } 4. Ba4 { [%clk 1:42:08] } 4... Nf6 { [%clk 1:42:08] } 5. O-O { [%clk 1:42:35] } 5... Be7 { [%clk 1:42:35] } 6. Re1 { [%clk 1:42:58] } 6... b5 { [%clk 1:42:57] } 7. Bb3 { [%clk 1:43:24] } 7... O-O { So far this is very standard. It's first now white has a choice. } { [%clk 1:43:21] } 8. h3 { One of the many anti-marshalls } { [%clk 1:43:39] } (8. c3 { this allows the marshall gambit which has been discussed to death in both high level and low level chess for ages. Still it seems to have stood the test of time and engines, and is on the repertoire to many very strong and aspiring chess players. } 8... d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5 c6 { and so forth. }) 8... Bb7 { [%clk 1:43:27] } 9. d3 { [%clk 1:43:49] } 9... d6 { [%clk 1:43:45] } 10. a3 { [%clk 1:44:09] } 10... Qd7 { [%clk 1:42:08] } 11. Nc3 { [%clk 1:43:12] } 11... Rfe8 { [%clk 1:41:08] } 12. Bd2 { Is a very weird and passive looking move. But as this game shown it must be taken seriously. } { [%clk 1:43:14] } (12. Bg5 { is a more natural square for the bishop. But on g5 it risks getting attacked and exchanged. White has a slight space advantage since both his bishops are outside the pawn chain. Generally this means that white wants to avoid exchanges. }) 12... Nd8 { [%clk 1:32:27] } 13. Nd5 { MVL doesn't care about my last comment about not exchanging pieces as he exchanges one pair of knights. But as we will see, this results in the knight on d8 being completely stuck. The exchange comes with a price for black. } { [%clk 1:42:33] } 13... Nxd5 { [%clk 1:24:50] } (13... Ne6 { Might be a better option } 14. Nxe7+ { White will have a small advatange due to the two bishops. But black is very solid and can start thinking about improving his pieces. Maybe with Nh5->Nhf4 }) 14. exd5 { [%clk 1:42:54] } (14. Bxd5 { would just help black. } 14... Bxd5 { Now black only has to find room for two light pieces. } 15. exd5 f5) 14... c5 { [%clk 1:22:34] } 15. a4 { [%clk 1:36:31] } 15... f5?! { This is probably too much. } { [%clk 1:14:13] } (15... f6 { Might be the saddest engine move I have ever seen. Black goes into total lockdown mode. No one enters, no one leaves.
One advantage of this is that it doesn't run into the tactics involving the b5 pawn we will see later. }) 16. axb5 { [%clk 1:25:54] } 16... axb5 { [%clk 1:14:36] } 17. Rxa8 { [%clk 1:26:19] } 17... Bxa8 { [%clk 1:15:03] } 18. c4! { Simply picking up the pawn on b5 due to tactics } { [%clk 1:22:03] } 18... Nf7 { [%clk 1:05:07] } (18... bxc4?? { wasn't a possibility, because of: } 19. Ba4) (18... Rf8 { black can't retake the pawn even if he avoids the skewer on a4. } 19. cxb5 Qxb5 20. Nxe5 { Boom! } 20... dxe5 21. d6+ $18) 19. cxb5 { white simply picks up a pawn creating a passed pawn and preparing to put a fat bishop on c4. } { [%clk 1:19:42] } 19... g5 { Ding is desperate for counter play so he tries to grab some space on the kingside to get some squares for his pieces. } { [%clk 1:05:22] } 20. Nh2! { Simple chess. Black might have been planning to go g4, so why not just avoid it. } { [%clk 1:14:29] } 20... Kg7 { [%clk 0:58:51] } (20... Qxb5?? 21. Ba4 { picks up material. }) 21. Bc4 { Black is probably just positionally lost. His pieces are just looking at each other. Meanwhile white can manouver around and find perfect squares and breakthroughs. } { [%clk 1:10:36] } 21... Kg6 { [%clk 0:59:01] } 22. g4! { [%clk 1:05:25] } 22... Nh6 { [%clk 0:57:18] } 23. Qf3 { [%clk 0:55:48] } 23... Bd8 { [%clk 0:57:22] } 24. Qg2! { Simple beautiful chess. On f3 the queen is blocking for a possible Nf3, and on g2 it eyes the g-file towards the king. } { [%clk 0:50:55] } 24... f4? { Black's last hope was to do nothing and pray that white doesn't find a way to break through. After f4 everything crumbles. But the position is probably just positonally lost no matter what. } { [%clk 0:55:27] } (24... Bb7 25. gxf5+ Nxf5 26. Nf3 h6 27. h4 { is less than ideal. Liren understandably tried to keep the kingside closed with f4. }) 25. b4! { Breaks open the queenside. MVL masterfully converts his advantage into a full point. } { [%clk 0:40:47] } 25... Bb6 { [%clk 0:39:58] } (25... cxb4 26. Qe4+ Kg7 27. Nf3 b3 28. d4 Bf6 29. Bc3 Nf7 30. b6 Qc8 31. dxe5 dxe5 32. Qd3 { is the engine line. Which seems equally hopeless. White's two passers and better pieces are gonna decide the game. }) 26. Qe4+ { [%clk 0:36:28] } 26... Kg7 { [%clk 0:39:50] } 27. bxc5 { [%clk 0:32:15] } 27... dxc5 { [%clk 0:40:12] } 28. Nf3 { [%clk 0:31:31] } 28... Nf7 { [%clk 0:40:34] } 29. Bc3 { Black can't keep an eye on both the passed pawns and keep everything under control, in the tight space he is allowed to operate in. } { [%clk 0:31:55] } 29... Bc7 { [%clk 0:38:19] } 30. b6! { Tightens the space even more. } { [%clk 0:29:51] } 30... Bb8 { If we simply count the amount of squares under each players control it's obvious that white is winning. } { [%clk 0:38:48] } (30... Bxb6 31. Nxe5 { the laser bishops aganinst the king will decide the game. } { [%cal Gc3g7,Gc4g8] }) 31. Qf5 { I found this move odd while watching it live. White has a strong ongoing attack so why would you exchange queens? But MVL seems to have just worked it all out to the very end and converts convincingly. } { [%clk 0:29:49] } 31... Qxf5 { [%clk 0:37:35] } 32. gxf5 { [%clk 0:29:41] } 32... Kf6 { [%clk 0:36:21] } 33. Nd2 { [%clk 0:24:28] } 33... Rd8 { [%clk 0:36:39] } 34. d6 { [%clk 0:17:00] } 34... Rxd6 { [%clk 0:35:20] } 35. Rb1 { [%clk 0:11:21] } 35... Nd8 { [%clk 0:35:07] } 36. b7 { [%clk 0:09:45] } 36... Bxb7 { [%clk 0:33:49] } 37. Ba5! { Black's pieces are overloaded. White wins heavy material. As a result Ding resigned. A masterful display by MVL. } { [%clk 0:10:06] } 1-0


