[Event "Norway Chess 2017: Carlsen - So"]
[Date "2017.06.06"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C50"]
[Opening "Italian Game: Giuoco Piano"]
[StudyName "Norway Chess 2017"]
[ChapterName "Carlsen - So"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/HwXovdRZ/eLtolzD4"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/lovlas"]
[UTCDate "2017.06.06"]
[UTCTime "13:33:32"]

{ This is the game the entire chess world have been waiting for. The world number one, Magnus Carlsen, takes on the number two, Wesley So. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 { The Italian has experience a surge in popularity the recent years. It has now overtaken the Spanish as whites go to opening after at the highest level. One of the advantages is that it avoids the Berlin Defense. It also a very flexible opening where White has a lot of different ideas to chose from. } (3... Nf6 { Is blacks other main option. With this black also reserves the option of playing Be7. But it also leaves white with additional options, f.ex. the very sharp 4.Ng5 }) 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. h3 { The most common sixth move is c3. However, the positions often transpose. h3 is a very flexible moves. It covers the g4 square and gives whites king some breathing room. At the same time it could allow white to maneuver one of his knight to g4 via h2. } 6... d6 7. c3 a6 { a6 has become the most popular way to play as black. It prepares b5 and gives black bishop an extra square on a7. The extra square can prove important if white continues with a4 and b4. } 8. a4 { White decides to grab some space on the queenside, while at the same time stopping b5. } 8... Be6 (8... Ba7 { is the most common move. Play usually follows } 9. Re1 Ne7 10. Nbd2 Ng6 11. Nf1 c6 12. Bb3 d5 { was played in Caruana - So, 2016. White failed to prove an opening advantage and the game eventually ended in a draw. }) 9. Bxe6 fxe6 { It is always hard to know if the doubled e-pawns will become a strength or a weakness. The e6 pawn could potentially become a target, and if black where to play d5, e5 might become weak. But at the same time it covers the important d5 and f5 square. It also allows black to keep two central pawns in the event of d4 exd4. The open f-file could also become important. } 10. b4 { so far the players have been following Nepomniachtchi - Yu, 2016. After } (10. d4 Ba7 11. Re1 exd4 12. cxd4 e5 { black equalized comfortably and the game ended in a draw after 40 moves. }) 10... Ba7 11. Be3 { White also decides to double his f-pawns. Objectively the position is probably about equal, but we all know what Magnus can do in "drawn" positions } 11... Bxe3 12. fxe3 { Whites only advantage is his space on the queenside. } 12... Ne7 { This same position was reached in Varga - Pinter, 2000. In that game white opted for quick play on the queenside with 13.c4 } 13. Nbd2 (13. c4 { However, after } 13... a5 14. b5 Ng6 15. Nc3 Qe7 16. Ra2 h6 17. Raf2 Rf7 18. g4 Nh7 19. Qe1 b6 { it became clear that white had no way to make progress. The game ended in a draw after 39 moves. }) 13... Ng6 { Black has successfully transferred his knight from c6 to g6. From here it is free to protect e5 without being annoyed by whites b-pawn. This could allow black to break in the centre with d5. Generally black is fine if successfully manages to play d5 in these types of positions. } 14. d4 (14. Kh1 { If white were to play something silly like Kh1 black can immediately break in the centre with } 14... d5) 14... Qe7 { Black finishes his development and prepares to fix his centre with exd4 and e5 or d5. } 15. Qb3 (15. Kh1 { Do not do this at home } 15... exd4 16. exd4 e5 { White cannot be better here. }) 15... Kh8 { renewing the idea of exd4 followed by e5 } 16. b5 { This is whites only hope for an advantage. White needs to find a way to weaken blacks pawn chain and put pressure on it. One idea could be to open the a-file and play b6. After that white can start piling pressure on the b7-pawn. } (16. Kh1 exd4 17. exd4 e5) 16... axb5 17. axb5 exd4 18. cxd4 { Carlsen decides to take with the c-pawn. exd4 looks more normal as it straightens out the e-pawns. But at the same time exd4 might allow black to simply play e5 followed by putting a fat knight on f4. } (18. exd4 Rxa1 19. Rxa1 e5 20. b6 c6 21. Ra7 h6 { White cannot easily put pressure on the b-pawn, without making a concession in the centre. }) 18... e5 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Rc1 exd4 21. exd4 Nxe4 22. Nxe4 Qxe4 23. Rxc7 { Out of nowhere we have reached an interesting and complex middlegame. White has an immediate threat of Qf7, threatening mate and hitting the b7-pawn. The idea of Ng5-f7 might also become a problem. } 23... Rf8 (23... Rb8 24. Qf7) 24. Qc2 Qd5 (24... Qxc2 25. Rxc2 Kg8 26. Nd2 { White plays to put pressure on the d6-pawn with Ne4. } 26... h6 27. Ne4 d5 28. Nc5 { it is obvious that white must be better. But it is unclear wether its enough to win }) 25. Qc4 Qxc4 26. Rxc4 { The advantage of exchanging queens on c4 instead of c2, is that white will run into a fork if he continued with Ne2 and Ne4 } 26... Kg8 { After the queen has been exchanged black is ready to bring his king into the play. } 27. b6 { white fixes the b-pawn. Black will have to find a way to keep both the b and d-pawn under control. } (27. Nd2 Nf4 28. Ne4 d5) 27... h6 28. Nd2 Nf4 { black cannot defending passively with moves like } (28... Rf7 29. Rc8+ Kh7 30. Rd8 Nf4 31. Rxd6 { white is a clear pawn up. }) (28... Rd8 29. Rc7 Rb8 30. Rd7 { white will grab the d-pawn, while his pieces remain active. }) 29. Rc7 Rf7 30. Nc4 Nd5 31. Rc8+ Rf8 32. Rxf8+ Kxf8 33. Nxd6 Nxb6 34. Nxb7 { Even though white wins a pawn, the position is still a technical draw. Black will simply use his king and knight to stop white from making progress with his d-pawn. } 34... Ke7 35. Kf2 Ke6 36. Ke3 Kd5 37. Na5 Na4 38. Nb3 Nb2 39. Nd2 Nd1+ 40. Ke2 Nb2 41. Nb3 Kc4 42. Nc5 { Magnus is such a sneaky trickster. Nc5 allows white to remain a pawn. } 42... Kxd4 43. Ne6+ Ke4 44. Nxg7 { But its clear that white cannot win with only one extra pawn. } 44... Nc4 45. Kf2 Kf4 46. g3+ Ke4 47. g4 Kf4 48. Nh5+ Kg5 49. Kg3 Ne5 50. Nf4 Kf6 51. Kh4 Ng6+ 52. Kg3 { So went into deep thought here. The resulting pawn endgame after 52...Nxf4 is not as easy to hold as it might look at first. } 52... Nxf4 53. Kxf4 Kg6 54. h4 Kf6 55. Kf3 { Again Magnus puts pressure on So. Amazingly there is only one move for black that holds. } 55... Kf7! { Black takes the long opposition. Moves such as } (55... Ke7 { woud lose } 56. Ke3 { now white has the long opposition and wins easily. } 56... Ke6 57. Ke4 Kf6 58. Kd5 { White starts a flanking maneuver. } 58... Ke7 59. Ke5 Kf7 60. Kf5 Kg7 61. Ke6 Kg6 62. Ke7 Kg7 63. h5 Kh7 64. Kf7 Kh8 65. Kg6 { 1-0 }) 56. Ke3 { Again there is only one move that holds } 56... Ke7! 57. Kd3 { Yet again black has to be careful. } 57... Kd7! 58. Kc4 Ke6! { Other moves would lose. } 59. Kd4 Kd6 60. Ke4 Ke6 61. Kf4 Kf6 62. Ke4 Ke6 63. Kf4 Kf6 64. Ke4 { 1/2 - 1/2
I doubt Carlsen was very happy with opening choice. But as always he managed to find a way to create problems for his opponent. So defended masterly and found his way through the maze. } *


[Event "Norway Chess 2017: Nakamura - Giri"]
[Date "2017.06.06"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D80"]
[Opening "Grünfeld Defense: Stockholm Variation"]
[StudyName "Norway Chess 2017"]
[ChapterName "Nakamura - Giri"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/HwXovdRZ/EetiNj6C"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/lovlas"]
[UTCDate "2017.06.06"]
[UTCTime "13:34:07"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is very modern response to the Queens Pawn opening. At first look it seems like black gives up the entire centre after 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e4. However, black will start adding pressure on the d4 pawn with Bg7 and c5. } 4. Bg5 { is a response you'll rarely see at the highest level in classical games these days. But this does not mean it is a poor choice. Already on move four white puts heavy pressure on the d5-pawn. } (4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 { is the most played line } 6... Bg7 7. Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O { has been played in over 2000 games. }) 4... Ne4 { is the most popular response. Even though the knight seem to leave the defense of the d-pawn it still covers it indirectly as it threatens both the knight on c3 and the bishop on g5. } 5. Bh4 (5. Nxe4 { is another logical option which was played in Morozevich - Carlsen, 2011. } 5... dxe4 6. Qd2 Bg7 7. e3 c5 { This is very typical of the Grünfeld. Black starts throwing pieces against d4. } 8. d5 Nd7 9. Ne2 (9. d6?! Qb6 10. Bxe7 Qxb2 { The engine loves black here. Black will probably continue with Bf6 in the near future. Then the pawn on d6 might become a liability for white. } 11. Qxb2 Bxb2 12. Rb1 Bc3+ 13. Kd1 Bf6) 9... Ne5 10. Nc3 f5 11. Be2 Nf7 12. Bh4 O-O 13. f3 exf3 14. gxf3 Qd6 15. Bg3 e5 16. O-O-O Bd7 17. Kb1 a6 18. e4 f4 19. Bf2 Rab8 20. h4 b5 { Lead to very doubled edged play in Carlsen - Morozevich, 2011. }) 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 dxc4 7. e3 (7. e4 { looks like the most natural move. However, this allows black to play b5 and defend his c4 pawn. } 7... b5 8. a4 c6) 7... Be6 (7... b5 8. a4 c6 9. axb5 cxb5 10. Qf3 { wins for white } { [%csl Ga8] }) 8. Qb1 b6 (8... Qd5 { is another option. } 9. Nf3 Nd7 10. Be2 Bf5 11. Qb2 Bg7 12. O-O Bd3 13. Bxd3 cxd3 14. Rfd1 Qe4 15. Qb1 c5 16. Rxd3 Rc8 17. a4 e6 18. Rd1 Qc6 19. Qb5 O-O 20. Rdb1 b6 { was played in Eljanov - Svidler, 2010. White is probably a bit better due to his solid centre and option to play a5 at a later stage. But its hard to find a clear way to proceed. }) 9. Nh3 { White wants to put his knight on f4 to put pressure on the bishop on e6 and the c4-pawn. The reason Nh3 is better than Ne2 will soon become clear. } 9... Bh6 { Nakamura surprisingly went into the tank here. This position is fairly well known and has been played a few times at the highest level, fex in Macieja - Navara, 2005. } 10. Bg5 { If the knight was on e2 this wouldnt be an option. } 10... Bxg5 { white would be clearly better after 10...Bg7 11.Nf4. } (10... Bg7 11. Nf4 { and black has problems defending his c4 pawn } 11... Bf5 12. e4 h6 13. Bh4 Qd6 14. Bg3 { gave white a clear advantage in Pashikian - Nechepurenko, 2006. }) 11. Nxg5 Qd5 (11... Bd5 { would run into } 12. e4 Bb7 (12... h6 13. Nf3 Bb7 14. Bxc4) 13. Bxc4 { white has a nice edge due to his control over the centre and active pieces. }) 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. Qb4 { is as far as I can tell a novelty. Previously only 13.Qb5+ has been played. } (13. Qb5+ c6 14. Qxc4 Qxc4 15. Bxc4 Nd7 16. a4 Rc8 17. Ke2 e6 18. h4 Ke7 19. Rhb1 Rc7 20. Bd3 c5 { white had a small endgame advantage in Shulman - Mikhalevski, 2006. But black managed to hold without too many issues. }) 13... Qd5 { discourages 14.Bxc4 as the g2 pawn would be left hanging. } 14. Qxc4 Qxc4 15. Bxc4 { White enjoys a nice edge due to his space advantage and bishop vs knight. But with correct play black should probably be able to hold. } 15... e6 16. Be2 Nd7 17. a4 Ke7 18. a5 { white grabs space on the queen side and tries to create a weakness. } 18... c6 19. Kd2 b5 20. Rab1 Rab8 21. Rb2 f5 22. Rhb1 { White starts adding pressure in the b-file. Later white could consider opening it with moves like a6 followed by c4. He could also add pressure on the c6 pawn with Bf3. } 22... Kd6 23. f3 e5 24. c4 exd4 (24... a6 { is another option. a6 looks like it stops everything but white still has ways to break through. } 25. d5 cxd5 26. cxb5 axb5 27. Rxb5 { it is clear that white is the one with winning chances here with a passed pawn on a5. }) 25. cxb5 cxb5 26. Bxb5 dxe3+ 27. Kxe3 Nf6 28. Bc4 Rxb2 (28... Rhe8+ 29. Kd4 Rbd8 { Keeping two rooks on the board might have been a better choice. Black can then proceed to cover the a7 pawn from the 7th rank. It is hard to see how white will make progress. }) 29. Rxb2 Re8+ 30. Kd4 Re7 31. Rb8 { blacks position is very difficult as his pieces have almost no squares. But its not easy to find a winning plan for white. } 31... Rd7 32. Rc8 { white continues to remove squares from blacks pieces. } 32... Rb7 33. a6 Rb4 (33... Rc7 34. Rxc7 Kxc7 35. Ke5 Nd7+ 36. Kf4 { should win for white. } { [%cal Gf4h6] }) (33... Rd7 34. Bb5 Re7 35. Rc6+ { picks up the knight on f6 }) 34. Kc3 Ra4 35. Kb3 Nd7 { protects the rook indirectly with the idea of Nb6 } 36. Bb5 Ra5 37. Kb4 Ra1 38. Rd8 { it might look like white is winning the knight on d7, but black survives by checking whites king to the c-file and then playing Rc7. } 38... Rb1+ 39. Ka5 Ra1+ 40. Kb4 (40. Ba4 Ke6 { saves the knight. } 41. Rxd7 Rxa4+ 42. Kxa4 Kxd7 { black will pick up the a6 pawn and win. } 43. Kb5 Kd6 44. Kb4 Kc6) 40... Rb1+ 41. Ka4 Ra1+ 42. Kb3 Rb1+ 43. Kc4 Rc1+ 44. Kd3 Rc7 45. Kd4 { and we are back to where we started 5 moves ago. } 45... Ke7 46. Ra8 Kd6 47. h4 Ke7?? { loses on the spot as black soon will find himself in zugzwang } 48. Bxd7! Rxd7+ 49. Ke5! Kf7 (49... Rc7 50. Rh8 Rc5+ 51. Kd4 Ra5 52. Rxh7+ Kd6 53. Rxa7 { is a technical win }) 50. Rb8 { now Rb7 is an unstoppable threat } { [%cal Gb8b7] } 50... Re7+ 51. Kd5 Kf6 52. Rb7 Re5+ 53. Kd4 Ra5 54. Rxa7 { is a technical win for white. White will simply play Ra8, put his king on a7 and go Rb8 Rb6 Kb7 followed by a7-a8. } 54... f4 55. Kc4 Ra2 56. Kc5 h5 57. Ra8 Rc2+ 58. Kb6 Rb2+ 59. Kc5 Rc2+ 60. Kb6 Rb2+ 61. Ka7 Rxg2 62. Rb8 Rf2 63. Rb6+ Kg7 64. Kb7 Rxf3 65. a7 Ra3 66. Ra6 Rb3+ 67. Kc6 { 1-0 } *


