1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 { The Queens gambit accepted. } 3. e3 Nf6 (3... b5 { it's worth noting that black cannot keep his pawn with 3...b5 } 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Qf3 { and black cannot save his rook on a8 } { [%csl Ga8] }) 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 { is a rare move. Usually white either plays Bb3 or dxc5. After b3 white prepares to put his dark squared bishop on the long a1-h8 diagonal. Sooner or later that diagonal will be opened by a pawn exchange in the centre. } (7. dxc5 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 { leads to the well known QGA endgame. Even though the position is almost entirely symmetrical white can try to claim an advantage. } 8... Bxc5 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Be2 Rd8 11. Ne5 Be7 12. Nec4 Nc6 13. Bf3 { gave white an edge in Georgiev - Rublevsky, 2004. }) (7. Bb3 Nc6 8. Nc3 cxd4 9. exd4 { Whites pieces are much more active. It is clear that he must have a slight edge even with an isolated queens pawn. } 9... Be7 10. Bg5 O-O 11. Qd2 Na5 12. Bc2 b5 13. Qf4 { lead to very interesting play Kramnik - Anand, 2001. }) 7... Nbd7 8. Bb2 b5 9. Be2 Bb7 10. a4 { this move forces black to make a commitment with his queen side structure. } 10... b4 (10... bxa4 11. Rxa4 Be7 12. Nbd2 Nb6 13. Ra5 cxd4 14. Bxd4 Nbd5 15. Qa1 { gave white a nice edge in Agdestein - Ehlvest, 1989. }) 11. Nbd2 Be7 12. Rc1 O-O 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Ne5 Rc8 { So far the players have been following Akesson - Van Wely, 1995. Where play followed 15.Nxd7 } 15. Bf3 (15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. Bf3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Be7 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 19. Rc1 Qd8 20. Ne4 f5 21. Qg3 e5 22. Nd2 { Here the players agreed to draw. }) 15... Nd5 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Nc4 { it is clear that white must be better. Blacks pawns on a6 and b4 can potentially become weak. At the same time white has a very strong bishop pair. But as always in the QGA blacks position is very solid, making it hard for white to find anything decisive. } 17... Qe7 18. Qe2 Ba7 19. g3 Bb8 20. Rfd1 Rfd8 21. Bg2 { Both players are shuffling their pieces around trying to improve them. } 21... Bc7 22. Qg4 f6 23. h4 (23. e4 { might have been a decent option } 23... Nb6 (23... Nc3 24. Bxc3 Rxd1+ 25. Qxd1 bxc3 26. Rxc3 Rd8 27. Rd3 { leaves white a pawn up in exchange for the bishop pair. Its hard to tell wether its enough to win. }) 24. Na5 Ba8 25. Bh3 e5 26. Qe6+ Kf8 27. Rxd8+ Qxd8 28. Nc6 { leaves blacks pieces cramped and his king exposed. } 28... Bxc6 29. Qxc6 { and black is losing material. }) 23... a5 24. Rd2 Ba6 25. Rdc2 Rb8 26. h5 { White grabs space on the kingside. In the future h6 might become a threat. } 26... Rd7 27. Qh4 (27. e4 { Again white could have grabbed a pawn with e4. } 27... Nc3 (27... Nb6 28. Nxa5) (27... Bxc4 28. exd5 Bxb3 29. Qxe6+ Qxe6 30. dxe6 { black is losing material } { [%csl Gd7,Gc7] }) 28. Bxc3 bxc3 (28... Bxc4 29. Bxb4 Rxb4 30. Rxc4 Rxb3 31. Bh3) 29. Rxc3) 27... Rf8 28. Bh3 Bb7 29. Bd4 Qf7 30. Rd2 h6 31. Qg4 Re8 32. Qg6 Red8 33. Bg2 Ba6 34. Be4 Qxg6 35. hxg6 Ne7 36. Bc5 f5 37. Bxe7 Rxe7 38. Bf3 Rxd2 39. Nxd2 Kf8 40. Rc5 Rd7 41. Nc4 Bxc4 42. Rxc4 { Almost every piece has come off the board. Black can now simply put his king on e7 and wait. } 42... Ke7 43. Rc6 Bd8 44. Be2 Rd6 45. Rxd6 Kxd6 { We have entered a opposite bishop endgame. Generally these endgames are draw unless one of the sides has a big advantage in some form. } 46. Bc4 e5 47. f4 Bb6 48. Kf2 exf4 49. gxf4 h5 50. Kf3 h4 51. Bf1 Ke6 52. e4 fxe4+ 53. Kxe4 Kf6 54. f5 Bd8 55. Bh3 Bb6 56. Bf1 Bd8 57. Bh3 Bb6 58. Bf1 { 1/2 - 1/2 } *


