1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 { The caro-kann advanced almost always lead to very interesting positions } 3... c5 4. Ne2 { This is a rare line more common is 4.dxc5 or 4.Nf3. One advantage over the Nf3 line is that after 4.Nf3 Nc6 5.c3 Bg4 6.h3 Bxg4 white can reply with the simple Bxe2. If the knight was on f3 white would have to ruin his pawn structure with gxf3 } (4. dxc5) (4. Nf3) 4... Nc6 5. c3 Bg4 6. h3 { another serious option would be 6.f3 } (6. f3 Bf5 7. dxc5 Nxe5 8. Nd4 Bd7 { lead to a crazy middlegame in Welling - Hermansson, 2001. }) 6... Bxe2 7. Bxe2 e6 { We have reached a typical french structure where black has managed to exchange his light squared bishop. Usually this will benefit black as his entire centre is placed on light squares. However, blacks light squared bishop can in many variations be a crucial defensive piece. } 8. O-O Qb6 { Black keeps adding pressure on the d4-pawn. White has no good way to defend it as 9.Be3 would hang the b2 pawn. } 9. dxc5 { seems forced } 9... Bxc5 10. b4 { This is very typical. If white does nothing black will simply develop the rest of his pieces and enjoy a perfectly fine position. White hopes that he will gain enough tempi to put black under pressure } 10... Be7 11. Be3 Qc7 12. f4 Nh6 { From here the knight can head to f5, or even f7 in some cases. At the same time it allows black to castle kingside. } 13. Na3 { The knight heads towards the lovely square on d4. From there it controls a lot of squares and might allow white to play f5 at a later stage. If white is able to successfully play f5 blacks position usually crumbles. } 13... a6 14. Bd3 O-O 15. Nc2 f6 { Anand decides that its time to break in the centre. This is move black has to play sooner or later. Otherwise whites space advantage would allow him to simply improve all his pieces and increase his advantage. } 16. Nd4 Nxd4 { forces a lot of exchanges. } 17. Bxd4 fxe5 18. Bxe5 Bd6 19. Bxd6 Qxd6 20. Qd2 Nf5 { black has successfully swapped a lot of pieces and solved his opening problems. The position is probably about equal } 21. Rae1 Rac8 22. Re5 Rf6 23. Rfe1 g6 24. Bxf5 gxf5 25. Qe3 Rc6 26. a4 Qc7 27. c4 Rxc4 28. Rxe6 Re4 29. Qg3+ Qg7 30. Re8+ Rf8 31. Qxg7+ Kxg7 32. R1xe4 fxe4 33. Rxf8 Kxf8 34. Kf2 d4 35. g4 Kf7 36. h4 h5 37. gxh5 Kf6 38. h6 Kg6 39. f5+ Kxh6 40. a5 Kh5 41. Ke2 { we have reached a pretty pawn endgame. Both kings are tied down and the position is a draw. } 41... Kh6 42. Kf2 Kh5 43. Ke2 Kh6 44. Kf2 { 1/2 - 1/2 } *


