[UTCTime "13:34:33"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Another Italian } 3... Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. a4 { 6.c3 is more common but a4 is definitely a decent option. White plans to grab space advantage on the queenside and at the same time harass blacks bishop on c5. } 6... a6 7. c3 { Kramnik used to play this line with c3 and a4 a lot when he was younger. } 7... d5!? { In general black should be fine if he successfully gets to play d5. 7...d5 seems critical, but it is clear that it doesn't solve all his opening problems as white can start piling pressure on the e5 pawn. } 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Nbd2 Kh8 { A nice prophylactic move. Blacks king leaves the a2-g8 diagonal freeing his f7 pawn. } 10. Re1 f6 11. d4 Ba7 (11... exd4 12. Nb3! Ba7 13. Nbxd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c6 15. a5 { gave white a very nice edge in Giri - Tomashevsky, 2016. Blacks queenside is tied down and white has a yuuuuge knight on d4 }) 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 fxe5 { We have reached a very imbalanced middlegame. On one side blacks e5 pawn is weak. But the f-file has been opened leaving whites king and the pawn on f2 under attack. } { [%csl Gf2] } 14. Nf3 c6 (14... Bxf2+! { would equalize on the spot. } 15. Kxf2 Qh4+ 16. Kg1 Qxc4 17. Nxe5 (17. Rxe5 Nf6 18. Bg5 Bg4 19. h3 Bxf3 20. Qxf3 Nd7 21. Re4 Qc5+ 22. Qe3 Rfe8 { Gave black a decent position in Zidy - Brodda, 2016. }) 17... Qc5+ 18. Qd4 Qxd4+ 19. cxd4 a5 { leaves black in a perfectly equal position }) 15. Bg5 (15. Bxd5 cxd5 16. Rxe5 Bg4 17. Be3 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Bxe3 19. Rxe3 { white is a pawn up and the pawn on d5 might be a weakness. But whites exposed king probably gives black enough counterplay. }) 15... Qb6? { The resulting endgame will be very difficult for black. } (15... Bxf2+ 16. Kxf2 Qxg5 17. Bxd5 cxd5 18. Qxd5 Bg4 19. Qxe5 Qg6 { Should be fine for black. White has en extra pawn but his king is under heavy fire. }) 16. Bxd5 cxd5 17. Be3 Qxb2 18. Bxa7 Rxa7 19. Qxd5 { White has much better and more active pieces. } 19... b6 (19... Qxc3?? 20. Qd6 { [%csl Gf8,Ga7][%cal Gd6b8] } 20... Rg8 21. Qb8 { wins heavy material }) 20. Rab1 Qxc3 21. Rxb6 Raf7 22. Qxe5 Qxe5 23. Rxe5 { White now has an extra pawn and more active rooks. the a6 pawn might also prove to be a liability for black. } 23... Bg4 { Black needs to activate his bishop if he is to survive the endgame. } 24. Re3 Kg8 (24... Bxf3 { it might be tempting to ruin whites king side structure but after } 25. Rxf3 Rc8 26. h3 { black will have troubles keeping his rooks active and defend the a6 pawn. } 26... Rxf3 27. gxf3 Ra8 28. a5 Kg8 29. Kg2 Kf7 30. Kg3 Ke7 31. Kg4 Ra7 32. h4 { This endgame should be winning for white. Black needs to stay passive allowing white to march his pawns and king up. }) 25. Ne5 (25. Rxa6 Bxf3 26. Rxf3 Rb8 27. h3 { This should also be close to winning for white as he is two pawns up. But rook endgames are never easy. }) 25... Rxf2 26. h3 Bc8 27. Nc6 Rf1+ 28. Kh2 R1f6 29. a5 { blacks queenside is tied down. } 29... h6 30. Ne7+ Kf7 31. Nc6 (31. Nxc8 Rxc8 32. Rf3 { looks strong. after a pair of rooks come off black will have to decide wether to sackrifice the pawn on a6 or have his own rook stuck defending it. With correct play there are probably decent drawing chances for black. }) 31... Kg8 32. Rc3 { Cheapo alert. } 32... Kh7 33. Ne7 Bd7 { Karjakin is as we all know immune to cheapos. } 34. Nd5 Rf5 35. Rd6 Bb5 { Karjakin has managed to improve his bishop from c8 to b5. It is no clear that black is fine. Even if white somehow managed to pick up the a6 pawn black would simply retake on a5. } 36. Nc7 Bf1 37. Rd7 Rf2 38. Rg3 R8f7 39. Rxf7 Rxf7 40. Rc3 Rf5 41. Rc1 Bd3 42. Rc3 Bf1 { 1/2 - 1/2. Karjakin shows off his defensive skills once again. } 1/2 - 1/2


