1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 { The Queens gambit declined } 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 c5 { is a sharp tarrasch line. Black will often find himself with an isolani on d5 in these lines. This pawn might become a target. The advantage is that blacks pieces will have a lot of squares and allow him easy development. } 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 exd5 { In general these position are slightly better for white due to the potential weakness on d5. Most endgames will be better for white. As a rule of thumb black wants to keep as many pieces are possible on the board. He especially does not want to exchange off the minor pieces. If only heavy pieces is left on the board white would triple in the d-line and prepare e4. White would also love to put a fat knight on d4. } 10. Bd3 Bb4+ { Forces white to misplace his knight or move his king. The main line follows } 11. Nd2 { The knight can no longer jump directly to d4, where it would become a blockading monster. } (11. Ke2 Nc6 12. Qc2 h6 13. Rhd1 Be6 14. Kf1 { it is clear that white must be better. The d5 pawn might prove weak. At the same time white has full control of the blockading square on d4. }) 11... Nc6 12. O-O Be7 { The lichess master database shows 7 games in this position. Everyone of them has ended with a draw. This might show that it is hard for white to find a way to increase his advantage. } 13. a3 Bf6 { From here the bishop controls the long a1-h8 diagonal where it keeps the important d4 square under fire. } 14. Nf3 (14. Rc1 Qe7 15. Nf3 Bg4 16. Rc2 Rad8 17. h3 Bh5 18. b4 d4 { Lead to equality in Tikhobaev - Silva, 2010. }) (14. Qc2 g6 15. Rac1 Be6 16. Nb3 Rc8 17. Nc5 Ne5 18. Bxe5 Bxe5 19. f4 Bg7 20. Nxe6 { gave white nothing in Kortchnoi - Kasimdzhanov, 2002. Black will no longer have an isolani, and all his pieces have become active. The players agreed to draw in this position. }) 14... Qe7 (14... Bxb2 { might look tempting, but after } 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Qc2+ Kg8 17. Qxb2 { blacks king has become a bit exposed. This combined with the isolani on d5 will give white a very pleasant edge. }) 15. h3 g6 16. Qd2 Be6 17. Rac1 Rfd8 18. b4 a6 19. Rc2 Qd7 20. Rfc1 Bf5 { In general black wants to keep his light pieces on the board. But its clear that his bishop is not doing much on e6, and is a weaker version of his counterpart on d3. } 21. Bxf5 Qxf5 22. Bc7 Rd7 23. Bb6 { From here the bishop defends the important d4-square and holds down blacks queen side pawns. } 23... Qe4 24. Rd1 Bd8 25. Bc5 Bc7 26. Qd3 Rad8 27. Rcd2 Qxd3 28. Rxd3 f6 { Ne5 might now be an idea. f6 also prepares the black king to marsh into the centre. After the queens has come off its time to include the king as well. Its very hard to see how white will make progress after black is able to bring his king to e6. } 29. b5 { White is hoping that he can create a weakness on the queen side. This combined with the exposed pawn on d5 might make blacks life much harder. } 29... axb5 30. Rb3 b6 { allows black to exchange his knight for whites dark squared bishop. But it comes at a price. After Rxb5 both the b6 and d5 pawn will become targets for whites active rooks. } (30... b4 { might have been a bit more accurate due to } 31. Bxb4 d4! 32. Rbd3 Bb6 { It is very hard to see how white will make progress without exchanging of one of blacks weaknesses. } (32... Ne5 33. Rxd4 Nxf3+ 34. gxf3 Rxd4 35. exd4) 33. exd4 Nxb4 34. axb4 Rd5 35. Kf1 Rc8 { [%cal Gc8c4] } 36. Ke2 Kf7 37. Rb3 Rd7 38. Ke3 Rc2 { blacks activity should compensate for the pawn. }) 31. Bd4 Nxd4 32. Nxd4 Bd6 33. Rxb5 Bxa3 34. Rxb6 Kf7 35. Rb5 h5 36. g4 hxg4 37. hxg4 Rc8 38. Kg2 Bf8 39. Kf3 Rcc7 40. Ne2 Rc5 41. Rb6 Rc8 42. Nf4 Rcd8 43. g5! Rd6 (43... fxg5 44. Ne6 Re8 45. Nxg5+ Kg7 46. Ne6+ Kf7 47. Nf4 { white will win a pawn. This combined with his activity and much better placed pieces should allow him decent winning chances. }) 44. Rb7+ R8d7 45. Rxd7+ Rxd7 46. gxf6 Kxf6 47. Kg4 d4 48. exd4 { Even though white is a full pawn up it is hard to see how we will win. Even so a Rook and Knight work very well together and black will have to thread carefully. } (48. Rxd4 Rxd4 49. exd4 { is a technical draw. Black will exchange of one pair of pawns and sacrifice his bishop on the last one. }) 48... Bc5 49. Ne2 Rd5 50. Kf3 Rf5+ 51. Ke3 Bf8 52. Ng3 Ra5 53. Kf3 Ra3+ 54. Kg4 Ra4 55. Ne4+ Kf7 56. f3 Be7 57. d5 Bf6 58. Rb1 Rd4 59. Rb7+ Kf8 60. Rb5 (60. d6 { might have been a better try } 60... Be5 61. Rd7 Rd1 62. Kg5 Rg1+ 63. Kh6 Bf4+ 64. Kh7 { looks very difficult for black. } 64... Be5 (64... Be3 65. Rc7 (65. Rb7 Bf4 66. d7 Ke7 67. Nc5 Rd1 68. Kxg6 Be3 { black will win the d7 pawn leading to a draw }) 65... Bf4 66. Ra7 Be3 67. d7 Ke7 68. Ra3 Bb6 69. Rd3 Bc7 { and black should still hold }) 65. Nc5 { the threat of Ne6 Ke8 Re7# forces black to give up material. } 65... Bxd6 66. Rxd6 { is a technical win }) 60... Be7 61. Kf4 Rd3 62. Nc5 Bd6+ 63. Ke4 Rd1 64. Nd7+ Ke7 65. Rb7 Re1+ 66. Kd3 Bh2 67. Nb6+ Kf6 { black has managed to improve the position of his king. It is now clear that the game should end in a draw. It is worth being aware of that R+N v R is an easy draw. } 68. Rh7 Bf4 69. Nc4 Kg5 70. Rf7 Rd1+ 71. Ke4 Re1+ 72. Kd4 Rd1+ 73. Kc5 Rc1 74. Kd4 Rd1+ 75. Kc5 Rc1 76. Kd4 Rd1+ 77. Kc5 Rc1 78. Kd4 { 1/2 - 1/2 } *


