1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 { Again the players opt for a Spanish opening. } 4... Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. a4 { The a4 anti-marshall. A few years ago almost every super grandmaster went for 8.c3 but after countless battles in the Marshall gambit it seems that they have decided that black is fine in those variations. } (8. c3 d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5 c6 { is the start position of the Marshall gambit. }) 8... Bb7 9. d3 { is usually played to make 9...d5 less attractive. After d5 white now will have total control over the d3 square, and his c1 bishop will be eyeing f4. } (9. c3 { leaves the d3-square weak enabling black to once again play d5. } 9... d5) 9... d5 { Carlsen doesn't care. The idea of playing d5 even when white does everything in his power to stop it was made famous by Gajewski. Carlsen previous encounter in a similar line was with black against Karjakin in the world championship match. That game also ended in a draw. } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nbd2 (11. Nxe5 { is the critical test. F.ex: } 11... Nd4 12. Nd2 Bd6 13. c3 Nxb3 14. Nxb3 c5 { Blacks strong bishops give him a lot of compensation. }) 11... f6 { defends the e5 pawn. One drawback is that if white gets to play c3 and d4 the f-pawn might find itself misplaced on f6. At the same time the a2-g8 diagonal has been opened. } (11... Nd4 { is another very thematic option. } 12. Nxe5 Bd6 13. c3 Nxb3 14. Nxb3 c5 { see note on move 11.Nbd2 }) 12. c3 Kh8 { Sidestepping the scary bishop on b3. } 13. axb5 axb5 14. Rxa8 Bxa8 15. Ne4 b4 (15... f5 { Magnus also considered this move for a long time. But concluded that this move would make his position too loose. } 16. Neg5 Qd6 17. Nh4 (17. Qe2 h6 18. d4 hxg5 (18... e4 19. Nxe4 fxe4 20. Qxe4 Nf6 21. Qd3 { white has a lot of compensation for the piece. } { [%cal Gf3h4,Gb3c2] }) 19. dxe5 Qd8 20. Nxg5 Bxg5 21. Qh5+ Kg8 22. Bxg5 Ne7 23. Qh4 { is a very interesting line. Even though white has sacrificed a piece for two pawns his active pieces and blacks exposed king seems to be enough to offer him more than full compensation. } 23... Rf7 24. Rd1 Qd7 25. Qd4 c6 26. e6 Qxe6 27. Qa7 { white will regain his material } 27... Rf8 28. Qxe7! Qxe7 29. Bxe7 Re8 30. Bc5 { white is a full pawn up and has much better pieces. }) 17... g6) 16. d4 bxc3 17. bxc3 exd4 18. Nxd4 { All the pawns in the centre has been swapped off. It is clear that white can't be better. } 18... Nxd4 19. cxd4 Bb4 20. Bd2 Bxd2 21. Qxd2 Re8 22. h3 Nb6 23. Nc5 Bd5 24. Bxd5 Nxd5 { After the bishops come off it is clear that the game will be heading towards a draw. } 25. Ne6 Qd7 26. Nc5 Qf7 27. Re2 Rb8 28. Re1 Re8 29. Re4 Rxe4 30. Nxe4 h6 31. Nc3 Qe6 32. Nxd5 Qxd5 33. Qe3 Kg8 34. Qe8+ Kh7 35. Qe3 c6 36. h4 Kg6 37. Qe8+ Kh7 38. h5 Qxd4 39. Qg6+ Kg8 40. Qe8+ Kh7 41. Qg6+ Kg8 42. Qe8+ Kh7 { 1/2 - 1/2 } 1/2 - 1/2


