1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 c6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg2 d5 6. b3 O-O { Historically black has been fine in these types of fianchetto Grünfeld positions. } 7. Bb2 (7. O-O Bf5 8. Bb2 Nbd7 9. Nbd2 Ne4 10. e3 Nxd2 11. Nxd2 Nf6 12. Qe2 Qd7 13. Rac1 Rac8 14. Nf3 Bg4 15. Qe1 Bh3 16. Ne5 { gave white a nice edge in Carlsen - Vachier-Lagrave, 2015. }) 7... c5!? { Vachier-Lagrave decides to break in the centre at once. } 8. dxc5 (8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. O-O Nc6 10. Qd2 Nc7 11. Rd1 cxd4 { gave white nothing in Villamayor - Gallagher, 2001. }) 8... dxc4 9. O-O Qc7 (9... Nc6 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bxe5 cxb3 13. axb3 { Whites space advantage on the queenside seems to give him a nice edge. But it is hard to make progress without exchanging off too many pieces. } 13... Nd5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Rd1 Be6 16. Ra4? (16. Bxd5 Rxd5 17. Rxd5 Bxd5 18. b4 a6 { should offer black full equality }) 16... Nf4! 17. Rd2 Nxg2 18. Kxg2 Bxb3 { was seen in Carnerio - Escalante, 2017. }) 10. Qc1 { a very pretty and instructional move. The queen leaves the open d-file while at the same time putting pressure in the c-fie. after cxb3 white would keep his strong c5 pawn. } 10... Qxc5 (10... cxb3 11. axb3 Nc6 12. Na3 Be6 13. Nb5 Qc8 14. Ng5 Bxb3 15. Ra3 Be6 16. Nxe6 fxe6 { Even though white has given up a pawn his activity and blacks weakness on e6 gives him a dominating position. } (16... Qxe6? 17. Nc7)) 11. Na3 Qh5 { black prepares to exchange his undeveloped light squared bishop for whites monster on g2. } 12. Nxc4 Nc6 13. Qg5 Qxg5 14. Nxg5 Bd7 15. Rfd1 Rfd8 16. Nf3 Be6 17. Nfe5 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Rd8 19. Rxd8+ Nxd8 { All the heavy pieces have disappeared. White still has an edge due to his much better minor pieces. But black has no weaknesses and will simply have to find a way to exchange some of the minor pieces. It is obvious that a draw is the most probable outcome. } 20. Nd3 Nd5 21. Ba3 Kf8 22. Nc5 Nc3 23. Nxe6+ fxe6 { It might seem strange to ruin your own structure. But white has no way to defend both his a2 and e2 pawn. In exchange for the pawn white can enjoy a strong bishop pair, and black is stuck with doubled e-pawns. } 24. Kf1 Nxa2 25. Na5 b6 26. Nc6 Nxc6 27. Bxc6 Be5 28. e3 Bd6 29. Bb2 (29. Bxd6?? { would be a huge mistake as it straightens blacks pain chain and gives up the bishop pair. } 29... exd6 { Is probably just winning for black }) 29... Nb4 30. Be4 Kf7 31. Ke2 Nd5 32. Bd3 e5 33. h4 Nf6 34. Bb5 e6 35. Bc6 Nd5 36. Kf3 h5 37. Ke4 Nf6+ 38. Kd3 { black has no way to make progress. } 38... Ng4 39. Ke2 Nf6 40. Kd3 Ng4 41. Ke2 Nf6 42. Kd3 Ng4 43. Ke2 { 1/2 - 1/2 } *


[Event "Norway Chess 2017: Anand - Kramnik"]
[Date "2017.06.06"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C78"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Morphy Defense, Neo-Arkhangelsk Variation"]
[StudyName "Norway Chess 2017"]
[ChapterName "Anand - Kramnik"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/HwXovdRZ/nAnAKmZL"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/lovlas"]
[UTCDate "2017.06.06"]
[UTCTime "22:49:18"]

{ Kramnik has never before beaten Anand with the black pieces in a classical game. This is kinda crazy considering that this is their 81 matchup }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 { The Spanish } 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5 { This variation is most commenly known as the archangel. Its usually reached by 5...b5 6.Bb3 Bc5. The main idea behind this move is to activate the bishop. In spanish openings it is usually stuck behind the pawns on e7. But from c5 it controls the long a7-g1 diagonal and attacks the very important d4 square. One drawback is that it wont be able to help in the defence of blacks king. White will often also gain a tempo as a future d4 will attack the bishop. } 6. Nc3!? { Is a very rare move. The idea is to play a quick Nd5 and create imbalances while harassing blacks pieces. The main line goes } (6. c3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. d4 Bb6 { This position has been reached countless times. It has been played a lot at the top level the recent years, especially by Nakamura who has used it with good results. }) 6... b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. Nd5 Nxe4 { Seems like the most critical response. Every time your opponent sacrifices a piece you should always ask yourself: "Ehm, why can't I just take it?" More often that not you can take it. The famous S. Agdestein usually says that to get a rating of 2000 you just need to take the hanging pieces. I am not sure if that also holds true for 2800. } (8... Nxd5 9. Bxd5 (9. exd5 Nd4 10. Nxe5 Bb7 { black will regain his pawn and enjoy a nice middlegame with his laser bishops. }) 9... Rb8 10. Bxc6 dxc6 11. Nxe5 Bd6 12. Nf3 { Looks a bit ugly for black. White is a pawn up but blacks bishop pair gives him some compensation. }) 9. d3 (9. Nxe5?? Nxe5 (9... Nxf2 10. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 11. Kxf2 Nxe5 { gg }) 10. d4 { might look tempting. But black has the very strong 9...Nxf2 }) 9... Nf6 10. Bg5 Be7! { Since black haven't played d6 yet he has reserved the option to play Be7. Otherwise his king side structure would be ruined. This retreat is something you often will see in Bc5 spanish line where white plays Bg5 before "tricking" black into playing d6. } 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 { Black is a solid pawn up. In return white has a very strong bishop pair. } 12. Re1 h6 13. Bh4 Bb7 14. c3 { a very typical move in these types of structures. After Bb7 black threatened to take away whites bishop pair with Na5. c3 gives his bishop the extra square on c2. At the same time it prepares a breakthrough in the centre with d4. } 14... Rfe8 { Kramnik knows that white will soon play d4. Re8 allows black to answer d4. It also puts a rook in the e-file might after d4 might be opened. } 15. d4 e4 16. Nd2 Na5 17. Bc2 g5 { breaks the pin. The pawn on e4 was hanging. } 18. Bg3 Nc4!? { A very interesting move. } 19. Nxc4 (19. Bxc7 Nxb2 20. Qb1 d5 { Leaves black with a dominant position. The bishop on c2 has almost no squares. At the same time black hasa large space advantage. The c3 pawn could potentially become a target. }) 19... bxc4 20. b3 { white decides to try and get rid of the annoying pawn on c4 that is holding his queenside pawns down. But this isnt as easy as it looks } 20... Bd5 21. Be5 { regains the pawn but leaves white in a worse endgame as blacks pieces are much more active. } 21... d6 22. Bxf6 Qxf6 23. bxc4 Bxc4 { Now the pawn is gone. But the bishop is still holding the pawns down. } 24. Rxe4 Rxe4 25. Bxe4 Re8 26. Bd3 Qe6 27. Bxc4 { Finally white gets rid of the annoying piece on c4. } 27... Qxc4 { Oh hello. A new annoying piece holding down whites queenside. } 28. Qb3 Qd3 29. h3 { creates luft to avoid back rank issues. it also keeps an eye on the g4 square. } 29... Kg7 { Simple chess. On g8 the king was exposed for back rank checks. On g7 it protects the important f6 square and h6 pawn. It is also worth noticing that there are currently no squares where the white queen could give a check without being taken. } 30. Rd1 Qe2 31. Rf1 Re6 { From here the rook can help launch a kingside attack, or maybe reach the queenside after playing d5. It also keeps an eye on the d6-pawn and, if we pretend the d6 pawn isn' there, the a6 pawn. } 32. Qd5 Qd2 33. Qc4 a5 34. Qxc7? (34. a4 { the passive defense is probably whites best option here. } 34... Re7 35. Qc6 Qd3 36. Ra1 f5 37. Rc1 { Even though blacks position is clearly preferable white should probably hold with accurate play. } 37... g4 38. hxg4 fxg4 39. g3 Qf3 40. Qb5 Rf7 41. Qf1 h5 42. Qe1 { White seems to have everything under control }) 34... Qxa2 { Now black has a terrifying passed a-pawn which white has big problems stopping. } 35. c4 Qd2 36. Qb6 a4 37. Qa7 Qb4 38. f4 { whites position is already hopeless. But after the rook comes off there is nothing he can do to stop the a-pawn. } (38. Kh2 { at least stops the Re1 rook exchange. } 38... Re1 (38... Re4 39. Ra1 Qb2 40. Qxa4 Qxf2 { leaves white in a world of pain. Black will grab at least one pawn. }) 39. Rxe1 Qxe1 40. Qxa4 Qxf2 41. Qd1 { holds easily for white }) 38... Re1 39. fxg5 Rxf1+ 40. Kxf1 hxg5 41. Kg1 Qxc4 (41... a3 42. Kh2 Qb2 43. Qa5 Kg6 44. Qa6 a2 45. Qxd6+ f6 46. Qf8 Qb7 47. Qg8+ Kf5 48. d5 a1=Q 49. Qe6+ Kg6 50. Qg8+ Qg7 51. Qe8+ Qf7 { might have been a cleaner route to victory }) 42. Kh2 Qb4 43. Qe7 Qd2 44. Qa7 Qf4+ 45. Kh1 Qc1+ 46. Kh2 a3 47. Qa5 Qf4+ 48. Kh1 Qc1+ 49. Kh2 Qe3 50. Kh1 f6 51. Qa4 Qc1+ 52. Kh2 Qf4+ 53. Kh1 Qe3 54. Kh2 Kf7 55. Kh1 Kg6 56. Qa8 Kg7 57. Qb7+ Kg6 58. Qa8 Qb3 59. Qe4+ Kg7 60. Qe7+ Qf7 { 0 - 1 } { Anand resigned as there is no way to stop the a-pawn from advancing. Kramniks first win against Anand with black in a classical game. } *


