1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. h3 d6 7. c3 { Kramnik this game decided to go for the classical Italian mainline. } 7... a6 8. Re1 Ba7 9. Bb3 h6 10. Nbd2 Re8 11. Nf1 Be6 12. Be3 { We are still in standard familiar territory. } 12... Bxe3 13. Nxe3 Qd7 { Usually white goes for either Nh4->f5 or Nh2->g4 here. But Kramnik has prepared another plan. } 14. Bxe6 (14. Nh4 Bxb3 15. axb3 Qe6 16. Nhf5 Kh7 17. Ng4 Ne7 18. Nxe7 Rxe7 19. Nxf6+ Qxf6 20. b4 { White has a space advantage on the queenside and can prepare to either launch an attack on the kingside or start expanding on the queenside. } 20... Rae8 21. Qg4 c6 22. Re3 Qe6 23. Qxe6 Rxe6 { game black a satisfactory position in Vatter - Gustafsson, 2009. }) 14... Qxe6 15. c4 { Is a very interesting rare idea White plans to simply go Nd5. This would force black to make a hard choice. Can he let the knight stay on d5, or must he allow white to open his c-file? } 15... Ne7 16. Nd5 Nexd5 (16... Nfxd5 17. cxd5 Qd7 18. d4 exd4 19. Nxd4 c6 20. dxc6 bxc6 { White can start putting pressure on blacks weak centre and the pawn on a6. It is clear that he must be better. }) 17. cxd5 Qd7 18. d4 c6 19. dxc6 Qxc6 20. Rc1 Qb6 21. Re3 exd4 22. Rb3 Qa5 23. Rxb7 Qxa2 { this allows So to double his rook on the f-file giving him the initiative. } (23... Rac8 { looks like an easier way to equality. } 24. Rxc8 Rxc8 25. Qxd4 Qxa2 26. Kh2 Qe6 { should be perfectly fine for black }) 24. Rcc7 Rab8 25. Rxf7 Rxb7 26. Rxb7 Rxe4 27. Rb8+ Kf7 28. Rb6 { all three of blacks pawn on the queenside are weak. } 28... a5 29. Qd3 d5 30. Rb7+ (30. g4 { might have been a strong option. g5 is now a treat } 30... Qc4 { looks natural but it allows a nasty trick. } (30... Kf8? 31. g5 hxg5 32. Nxg5 Re1+ 33. Kh2 Qb1 34. Rb8+ Ke7 35. Rb7+ Ke8 36. Qb5+ { is very dangerous for black }) 31. Qxe4 Nxe4 32. Ne5+ Ke7 33. Nxc4 dxc4 34. Ra6 { The exchange should offer white good winning chances. }) 30... Kg8 31. Rb8+ Re8 32. Rb7 Re4 33. Nxd4 Qc4 34. Qxc4 dxc4 35. Nf5 { Blacks pawn structure is broken and his kingside is exposed. It is clear that white must be better. } 35... Re5 36. g4 Ne8 37. Kg2 Rc5 38. Ra7 Nc7 39. f3 Ne6 40. Re7 Re5 41. Re8+ Kh7 42. Kf1 Kg6 43. Nd6 Kf6 44. Ne4+ Kf7 45. Nd6+ Kf6 46. Nxc4 { White seems to have won a pawn. However, blacks pieces will become very active making it impossible for Kramnik to make progress. } 46... Rc5 47. Ne3 Rb5 48. Nc4 Rc5 49. Ne3 Rb5 50. Nd1 Rb3 51. Kf2 Kf7 52. Ra8 Ng5 53. Rxa5 Rxf3+ 54. Kg2 Rd3 55. Nf2 Rd2 56. Rf5+ Ke6 57. b4 Rb2 58. Rf4 Ke5 59. Rf8 Kd6 60. Rf4 Ne6 61. Re4 Kd5 62. Re3 Rxb4 { white can no longer pretend to be better. } 63. Kg3 Rd4 64. h4 Rc4 65. Nd3 Re4 *


[Event "Norway Chess 2017: Aronian - Giri"]
[Date "2017.06.08"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
