[Opening "Queen's Gambit Declined: Ragozin Defense, Alekhine Variation"]
[StudyName "Norway Chess 2017"]
[ChapterName "Aronian - Giri"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/HwXovdRZ/snTrXOvX"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/lovlas"]
[UTCDate "2017.06.08"]
[UTCTime "12:38:09"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 { Another Ragozin. The same opening was played in Nakamura - Aronian in round 2. } 5. Qa4+ (5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 O-O 7. e3 Bf5 8. Qb3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Bd3 c6 12. Bxf5 Qxf5 { Didn't give Nakamura much. }) 5... Nc6 { is the only move that doesn't lose material. } 6. e3 O-O 7. Qc2 Re8 8. Bd2 a6 { so far we have been following Karjakin - Carlsen, 2016. Blacks plan is to take on c4 the second white moves his light squared bishop. } 9. h3 { is a useful waiting move. White want to improve his position as much as possible before moving his light squared bishop. Hoping to save a tempo } 9... Bd6 10. a3 Bd7 { Black marginally improves his bishop again waiting for whites light squared bishop to move before taking on c4. } 11. Be2 { White has no more useful moves other than moving the bishop. } 11... dxc4 { Finally black can take on c4. } 12. Bxc4 h6 13. O-O e5 { Generally in this types of position black is fine if he manages to break with e5 or c5. } 14. Rae1 Qe7 15. Nh4 { if black isn't careful he might trap his own queen. } 15... Qd8 { it is not clear what the knight on h4 is really doing. Black is threatening to simply take on d4. } (15... Rad8?? 16. Ng6 { [%csl Ge7] }) (15... Qf8?? 16. Ng6) 16. Qb3 { seems to grab a pawn. But the b7 pawn is indirectly guarded by the powerful Na5 move. } 16... Rf8 { now Na5 is a threat. } 17. Qd1 (17. Ng6 { Doesn't really work because of } 17... Na5 18. Qa2 Nxc4 19. Qxc4 Re8) 17... b5 18. Ba2 Kh8 19. Bc1 g5? { at first this seems to gain a lot of tempi on the knight. But Aronian has a trick up his sleeve. } (19... e4! { now the knight on h4 has no squares. } 20. Qc2 g5 21. f3 gxh4 22. fxe4 { leads to a crazy middlegame. White has two pawns for a knight. In return he has a massive centre. } 22... Bxh3 23. gxh3 (23. Re2 Rg8 24. Bxf7 Rg7 25. Nd5 { it is impossible to tell who is better. Everything is hanging. }) 23... Rg8+ 24. Kh1 Rg3 { is crushing } { [%csl Gh3][%cal Gd8d7,Ga8g8] }) 20. dxe5 (20. Nf3 g4 21. hxg4 Bxg4 22. Bb1 Rg8 { looks dangerous for white. }) 20... Nxe5 21. f4! gxh4 22. fxe5 Bxe5 23. e4! { Suddenly blacks kingside has been opened. White can consider ideas like Qd2, Rf3 followed by Ref1, or Nd5. } 23... Rg8 { hitting the g-file. Black needs to create counter play before his kingside gets destroyed. } 24. Bxf7 (24. Bf4! { forcing the exchange the e5 bishop followed by doubling in the f-file seems very strong. } 24... Bxf4 (24... Bxh3?? 25. Bxe5 { wins a lot of material }) 25. Rxf4 Bxh3 26. Qxd8 Raxd8 27. Kh2 Nh5 28. Rxh4 Bg4 29. Bxf7 Rg5 { Blacks pieces are uncoordinated and will struggle to stop the passed e-pawn. White must be better. } 30. e5 { black has to defend perfectly to avoid losing. } 30... Rd2 31. Ne4 Bf3! 32. Rxh5! { The white king needs the h3 square. } 32... Rgxg2+ 33. Kh3 Rde2 34. Rxe2 Rxe2 35. Rxh6+ Kg7 36. Ng3 Kxh6 37. Nxe2 Bxe2 { and black can probably hold. }) 24... Rg7 25. Bf4 Bxf4 26. Rxf4 { Aronian only had 90s left for the remaining 14 moves. } 26... Bxh3 27. Kh2 Bd7 { black has the nasty threat of Ng4+ followed by Qg5 with a crushing attack. } 28. Be6 (28. a4?? Ng4+ 29. Kh1 Qg5 30. Ref1 (30. Nd5 Qxf4 31. Nxf4 Nf2+ { black wins material }) 30... Ne3) 28... Ng4+ 29. Rxg4 Bxe6 30. Qxd8+ Rxd8 31. Rxh4 Kh7 { The material is now equal. Blacks bishop on e6 prevents the e-pawn from advancing, and the rook on d8 is ready to penetrate whites position. } 32. Re2 Rd4 33. Rf2 Rf7 34. Rxf7+ Bxf7 35. Rf4 Kg7 36. Rf5 Rc4 37. Kg3 c5 38. Kf3 b4 39. axb4 cxb4 40. Nd5 { Aronian miraculously survived to move 40. But did not manage to keep his advantage. } 40... b3 41. Ne3 Rd4 42. Ra5 Bg6 43. Nf5+ Bxf5 44. exf5 Rd2 45. Rxa6 Rxb2 { is a technical draw. } 46. Rg6+ Kh7 47. Rb6 Rb1 48. Rb7+ Kg8 49. g3 b2 50. Kg2 (50. Kf2?? { Would be an unfortunate mistake. } 50... Rh1 { [%cal Gb2b1] } 51. Rxb2 Rh2+ 52. Kf3 Rxb2) 50... Kf8 51. Kh2 Kg8 52. Kg2 Kf8 53. Kh2 Kg8 { 1/2 -1/2 } *


