1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 { The petroff used to be black players go to drawing weapon against 1.e4 before the rise of the Berlin wall. } 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 { is the old main line } (5. Nc3 { has been the most popular response to the petroff at the highest level the recent years. White will enjoy an open d-file and easy development. Later he can decide wether he wants to attack on the queenside or kingside } 5... Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 Nc6 8. Qd2 Be6 9. O-O-O Qd7 10. Kb1 Bf6 11. h3 h6 12. b3 a6 13. g4 O-O-O 14. Bg2 g5 15. Nd4 { gave white an edge in Caruana - Ponomariov, 2014. }) (5. d3 Nf6 6. d4 { is a tricky move orders often used by Carlsen. } 6... d5 { The position is symmetrical. Whites only advantage is that he is a half tempo up. }) 5... d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O { The position is almost entirely symmetrical. } 8. c4 c6 9. Re1 Bf5 10. Qb3 Qd7 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. Bxf5 Qxf5 13. bxc3 b6 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Qb5 Qd7 { so far we have been following Adams - Morozevich, 2005 and Ganguly - Saptarshi, 2006. } 16. Rb1 { is a very natural move. The simple idea is to retake on b5 with the rook, attacking the d5 pawn. } (16. a4 Rd8 (16... Nc6 17. c4 a6 18. Qxd5 Nb4 19. Qe4 Rae8 20. Qb1 Rxe1+ 21. Nxe1 Qc7 22. Bf4 Bxf4 23. Qxb4 Bxh2+ { gave black full equality in Ganguly - Saptarshi, 2006. }) 17. g3 Bc7 18. Bg5 f6 19. Bd2 Nc6 20. c4 Ne7 21. Rac1 a6 22. Qxd7 Rxd7 23. c5 { gave white an edge in Adams - Morozevich, 2005. }) (16. Qxd5?? { would be an awkward blunder } 16... Bxh2+ 17. Kxh2 Qxd5) 16... Rc8 17. g3 Bf8 (17... Rxc3?? 18. Re8+ Bf8 19. Qxd7 Nxd7 20. Rxa8) 18. Bd2 Nc6 19. Ne5 Nxe5 20. Rxe5 Rd8 21. Qxd7 Rxd7 22. Rb5 { puts additional pressure on the d5-pawn and prepares to play a4-a5 and create pressure on blacks queenside structure. } 22... Rad8 23. a4 Be7 24. a5 bxa5 25. Rxa5 { now white has two weak pawns to attack. It is clear that he must be a bit better. } 25... f6 26. Re6 Rb8 27. Rea6 Rbb7 { it is hard to see how white will improve if black sits back and does nothing. } 28. Kf1 Kf7 29. Ke2 Bd8 30. Ra2 Bb6 31. Bc1 Rbc7 32. Kd3 Re7 33. Bf4 Rc8 34. Bd6 Re1 35. Bc5 Bxc5 36. dxc5 Rxc5 37. Rxa7+ Kg6 38. R7a5 Rxa5 39. Rxa5 { we have entered a materially equal rook endgames. } 39... Rf1 40. f4 Rd1+ 41. Kc2 Rh1 42. Rxd5 Rxh2+ 43. Rd2 Rxd2+ 44. Kxd2 Kf5 45. Ke3 h5 46. Kf3 g5 47. fxg5 fxg5 48. g4+ hxg4+ 49. Kg3 Ke4 50. Kxg4 Kd3 51. Kxg5 Kxc3 { 1/2 -1/2 } *


[Event "Norway Chess 2017: Karjakin - Anand"]
