[UTCDate "2017.06.08"]
[UTCTime "12:38:29"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 { The first Berlin of the tournament! } 5. Re1 (5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 (6. dxe5 Nxb5 7. a4 { is a cute line. The knight on b4 is trapped. White will regain his material but can't really pretend to have an advantage. } 7... Nbd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 d5 10. exd6 Qxd6 11. Qe4+ Qe6 { is equal }) 6... dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 { Is the starting point of the infamous Berlin Wall. White has tried to break down for many years, but to this day it still remains one of blacks go to drawing weapons. }) 5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 { Re2 MC-Karj } 10. Re1 (10. Re2 { Carlsen played this sneaky move against Karjakin the world championship match. It might look mysterious but the idea is very simple. After black plays Re8 Rxe2 white reserves the option to recapture with the bishop allowing the queen to stay on d1 and defend the d4 pawn. } 10... Re8 (10... b6 11. Re1 { was seen in Carlsen - Karjakin, 2016. }) 11. Bf4 Rxe2 12. Bxe2) 10... Re8 11. Bf4 Rxe1 { In contrast to the Re2 line white now has to recapture with his queen, sacrificing the d4 pawn. } 12. Qxe1 Ne8 (12... Bxd4 { was an option, but after } 13. c3 Bf6 14. Bxd6 cxd6 { blacks pawn structure is ruined. White will simply develop his pieces and start hitting the weak d-pawns. It is clear that white must be better. }) 13. Nc3 { again white decides to give up the d-pawn. } 13... Bxd4 14. Nd5 d6 (14... c6 { is another option. } 15. Ne7+ Kf8 16. Nxc8 Qf6 17. Qb4+ c5 18. Qd2 Rxc8 19. c3 Be5 20. Bxe5 Qxe5 21. Qxd7 Qc7 22. Rd1 Qxd7 23. Rxd7 Rc7 { lead to an equal endgame in Kasimdzhanov - Leko, 2012. }) 15. Bg5 { black needs to play accurately, otherwise he might find himself under heavy pressure. } 15... f6 (15... Qd7? 16. Qe4 Bxb2 17. Ne7+ Kh8 18. Bd3 g6 19. Qd5 Qe6 20. Qb5 { wins material. } { [%csl Gb2,Ge8] }) 16. Bh4 { seems to be a novelty. } (16. Be3 Be5 17. f4 Bxb2 18. Rb1 Ba3 19. Qa5 { was seen in Andreikin - Jakovenko, 2016. But it seems that black should be fine after } 19... Be6 20. Bc4 c6 21. Qxa3 cxd5 22. Bd3 b6) 16... Bxb2 17. Rb1 Be5 18. f4 c6 19. fxe5 cxd5 20. exf6 Nxf6 21. Bd3 Bd7 22. h3 b5 23. Bxb5 Qe8 { Anand seems to have done his homework and equalized without too many problems. } 24. Qxe8+ Bxe8 25. Ba6 Bg6 26. Bxf6 gxf6 27. Bb7 Re8 28. Bxd5+ Bf7 29. Bxf7+ Kxf7 30. Rb7+ Kg6 31. Rxa7 Rc8 32. Rd7 Rxc2 33. Rxd6 Rxa2 { 1/2 - 1/2 } *


