[Event "Norway Chess 2017: Aronian - Carlsen"]
[Date "2017.06.10"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D45"]
[Opening "Semi-Slav Defense: Accelerated Meran Variation"]
[StudyName "Norway Chess 2017"]
[ChapterName "Aronian - Carlsen"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/HwXovdRZ/HTGVGJiu"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/lovlas"]
[UTCDate "2017.06.10"]
[UTCTime "09:38:30"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 a6 { is an interesting line. It is a hybrid between the semi slav and the a6 slav. } 6. b3 Bb4 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Qe7 (9... Bd6 { was played by Carlsen in the world rapid championship against Flores. } 10. Rc1 h6 11. Qc2 Re8 12. h3 Qe7 13. c5 Bc7 14. e4 e5 15. Rfe1 Qd8 16. exd5 cxd5 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Rxe5 19. Rxe5 Bxe5 20. Na4 Be6 21. Qd1 Ne4 22. Be3 Qh4 23. c6 bxc6 24. Rxc6 d4 25. Qc2 dxe3 { 0-1 Flores - Carlsen, 2016. }) 10. Bc2 $146 { A very odd looking move. At first it looks like a useless tempo loss. However, there are some interesting ideas behind this moves. white now can play e4 in many lines, without dxc4 threatening the bishop on d3. } 10... Rd8 11. a3! Bxa3 (11... Bd6 { Is probably what Carlsen should have played. } 12. e4 { black now has to take on e4. } 12... dxc4 (12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Nf6 15. Bg5 (15. Qe2 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 { must be a bit better for white }) 15... h6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Qe2 { white must be better. }) 13. e5 { illustrates one of the ideas behind 10.Bc2. As the bishop is no longer attack after dxc4, white has the very strong e5. }) 12. Rxa3! { A very strong exchange sacrifice. After this the black queen will struggle to get back into the game. At the same time blacks bishop on c8 will have a hard time finding a good square. } 12... Qxa3 13. c5! { White has the simple but deadly threat of Nb1 Qa2 Qc1, followed by Nc3. } 13... b6 { black is forced to try to get his queen out. } (13... h6 14. Nb1 Qa2 (14... Qb2 15. Bc3 Qa2 16. Re1 (16. Bb4 a5 17. Nc3 Qb2 18. Na4 Qa2 19. Bb1 Qa1 20. Bh7+ { wins on the spot }) 16... Ne4 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Re2 Qxe2 19. Qxe2 exf3 20. Qxf3) 15. Qc1 $13 { [%cal Gb1c3] }) 14. b4 (14. Nb1 Qa2 (14... Qb2 15. Bc3 Qa2 { after this blacks queen is doomed to spend the rest of her days on a2. Allowing white to whatever. } 16. Re1 bxc5 17. Re2 { wins on the spot. } { [%cal Gc2h7] }) 15. Qc1 bxc5 16. Nc3 Qa5 17. Nxd5 Qb5 18. Nc7 Qb8 19. Nxa8 Qxa8 20. Ba5 Re8 21. dxc5 { was another strong possibility. There is no doubt that white is much better here. }) 14... Ne4 { Carlsen tries to give back material in order to bring his queen back out. } (14... Qxb4 { doesn't work. } 15. Nxd5 Qc4 16. Ne7+ Kf8 17. Bb3 Qb5 18. Ba4 Qb2 19. Nxc6 Re8 20. Nfe5 { is probably also just winning. }) 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Bxe4 Rb8 (16... bxc5 17. Bxc6 Ra7 18. bxc5 a5 19. Qa1 Qxa1 20. Rxa1 { This endgame looks hopeless for black. The pawn on a5 is under heavy fire. At the same time white has a very powerful centre. }) 17. Bxh7+! { A powerful blow breaking open blacks kingside. } 17... Kxh7 18. Ng5+ Kg8 19. Qh5 Nf6 20. Qxf7+ Kh8 21. Qc7! { Blacks pieces are uncoordinated, allowing white to claim back some material. } 21... Bd7 22. Nf7+ Kh7 23. Nxd8 Rc8 24. Qxb6 Nd5 { black seems to win material. But due to his uncoordinated pieces he is unable to hold on to it. } 25. Qa7 Rxd8 26. e4 Qd3 27. exd5 Qxd2 28. Qc7 Qg5 29. dxc6 (29. d6 { Might have been even better } 29... Qf6 30. h3 { it is always nice to have some luft } 30... Qf8 31. Ra1 { black will lose a pawn. White can start pushing on the queenside or bring his rook to the kingside to start a deadly attack. The game is in white's hands. } { [%csl Ga6,Gc6] }) 29... Bc8 { White has four pawns for a piece, but it's difficult to march them forward. On the other side the black bishop on c8 is close to worthless. It is clear that white has the upper hand. } 30. h3 Qd5 31. Rd1 e5? (31... Rf8 { was probably a better try. } 32. Rd3 Qe4 33. Rg3 Qxd4 34. Kh2 Rxf2 35. Rg4 Qf6 36. Qxc8 Qe5+ 37. Rg3 Rxg2+ 38. Kxg2 Qe2+ { leads to a perpetual }) 32. Rd3! { black now has no way to deal with white's kingside attack. } 32... exd4 33. Qe7 Bf5 34. Rg3 Bg6 35. Qh4+ { 1 - 0 } { black loses material and the game. What a stunning game by Levon Aronian. } *


[Event "Norway Chess 2017: Nakamura - Vachier-Lagrave"]
[Date "2017.06.10"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B90"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Najdorf Variation"]
[StudyName "Norway Chess 2017"]
[ChapterName "Nakamura - Vachier-Lagrave"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/HwXovdRZ/uZtVwmyR"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/lovlas"]
[UTCDate "2017.06.10"]
[UTCTime "09:38:39"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 { Both Nakamura and MVL has been playing the Najdorf Sicilian at the highest level for a long time. It is clear that any game in this line between these two will have theoretical importance. } 6. Bd3 { Nakamura plays a rarer line. Probably trying to avoid a theoretical battle, but rather get a playable position. } (6. g3) (6. a3 e5 7. Nf5 { was seen in Carlsen - Wojtaszek. }) 6... e5 { is the most natural response. } (6... e6 { is another natural response in the najdorf. } 7. O-O Be7 8. Kh1 O-O 9. f4 Qc7 10. Qe2 Nbd7 11. Bd2 Nc5 { This typical Najdorf position has been reached a number of times at the highest level. Black will put his bishop on b7 on break in the centre. Meanwhile, White will try create something either in the centre or on the kingside. }) 7. Nde2 { the standard move. Compared to the g3 najdorf lines the knight now has the g3 square to its disposale. } (7. Nf5 { this idea has recently become popular. But it doesn't make much sense after 6.Bd3 } 7... Bxf5 8. exf5 d5 9. Bg5 Bb4 { leaves black in good shape compared to the Carlsen - Wojtaszek } 10. O-O Nc6 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Qg4 { was perfectly fine for black in Grischuk - Nepomniachtchi, 2013. } 12... Qa5 13. Nd1 Bd2 14. c3 h5 15. Qe2 Bg5) (7. Nb3 { is another natural move }) 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Ng3 { An interesting line. From here the knight controls the important f5-square. } 9... Be6 { Sooner or later black will break with d5. } 10. Nd5 { Nakamura decides to put his knight on d5. This forces black to make a decision. Should he exchange off his bishop or knight? } (10. Kh1 Nc6 11. Qe1 g6 { Didn't give white anything in Brajic - Nestorovic, 2007. }) 10... Bxd5 { Vachier-Lagrave decides to take with the bishop. } (10... Nxd5 11. exd5 Bc8 { looks ugly. } 12. f4! { if white does nothing black will play f5 and be perfectly fine. Now f5 would drop a pawn } 12... f5 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Nxf5 $18) (10... Nbd7 { might also have been an option. This allows white to take on e7 whenever he wants, removing an important defender of the d6-pawn. }) 11. exd5 g6 { A very natural move. Black takes away squares from the white knight, and at the same time thblocks e d3-h7 diagonal. The drawback is that it weakens the black squares around the king. If black found a way to put his bishop on g7 he would probably be perfectly fine. } (11... Nxd5 12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 13. Qxd5 { is usually a bit better for white. He can start putting pressure on the d6-pawn. }) 12. c4 Ne8 { black prepares to push f5. } (12... Re8 { with the idea Bf8->g7 also looks natural. But in general black wants to keep his rook on f8, protecting f7 and planning f5. }) (12... Nbd7 { To me this looks like the most normal move. } 13. Bh6 (13. b4 a5 { would leave white with some issues as he cannot play a3. }) 13... Re8 14. f4 (14. b4 a5 15. a3 axb4 16. axb4 Rxa1 17. Qxa1 b5! { white's centre will become weak. })) 13. Bh6 { white develops his last piece with a tempo. } 13... Ng7 14. b4 Nd7 (14... a5 15. a3 axb4 16. axb4 Rxa1 17. Qxa1 b5? { b5 here doesn't work as white is in time to grab the pawn and consolidate his centre. } 18. cxb5 Nd7 19. Qa7 Nb6 20. Qb7! $18) 15. Rc1 { white prepares to break with c5. If white managed to play c5 black would be in a world of hurt. } 15... a5 { black decides to break on the queenside } 16. a3 (16. b5? { is a big positional error as it would leave the c-pawn behind, and give black the c5-square. }) 16... axb4 17. axb4 Ra3 18. Ne4 { c5 is now a threat } 18... f5 { Usually black is fine after he is able to play f5. However, here his knight on g7 is misplaced, and white will soon be able to push c5. } 19. Nc3 e4 20. Be2 Bg5 21. Bxg5 Qxg5 22. c5! (22. Nb5 Ra6 23. Nd4 { also looks tempting for white. } 23... Ne5 24. c5 f4 25. f3 $16) 22... Ne5 (22... dxc5 23. bxc5 Nxc5 24. Nb5 { picks up material }) 23. c6! { a passed pawn is a happy pawn. } 23... Nh5 { black has no other choice than to try a kingside attack. But white's pieces are perfectly placed to deal with it. } 24. Bxh5 gxh5 25. Kh1 { Nakamura moves his king out of the open g-file and stops Nf3 ideas. It is clear that black's attack won't amount to anything. White's passed pawn will prove decisive. } (25. cxb7 Ra7 26. Nxe4 fxe4 27. Rc7 { is the engine line. White now threatens b8 picking up material. }) 25... Qh4 26. Qd4 Ng4 27. h3 f4 28. Kg1 { Simple chess. Again Nakamura steps out of the pin avoiding all counterplay. } 28... e3 29. hxg4 hxg4 30. cxb7 exf2+ 31. Rxf2 g3 32. Rxf4 Qh2+ 33. Kf1 { 1 - 0 } { black could try to give a few checks but the king will be safe on d3. } *


[Event "Norway Chess 2017: Giri - Anand"]
[Date "2017.06.10"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A21"]
[Opening "English Opening: King's English Variation, Kramnik-Shirov Counterattack"]
[StudyName "Norway Chess 2017"]
[ChapterName "Giri - Anand"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/HwXovdRZ/jUjFIVpJ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/lovlas"]
[UTCDate "2017.06.10"]
[UTCTime "09:38:48"]

1. c4 { Giri keeps putting faith in the English. Anand has struggled in the recent past again this. } 1... e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 { Seems to have become Anands go to line against the English. } 3. Nd5 Bc5 4. e3 Nf6 5. b4 { White decides to grab space on the queen side with tempo. The downside is that the pawns might become vulnerable. } 5... Nxd5 6. bxc5 (6. cxd5 { Can't be very good. } 6... Bxb4 7. Bb2 d6?? (7... Qe7 8. Nf3 Bd6 { black will castle, then put his light squared bishop on b7 and maybe his knight on c5. He can also get some initiative on the kingside with 0-0 and f5. }) 8. Qa4+ { is a typical cheapo. }) 6... Nf6 7. Nf3 { There are no games in the master database after this move. } (7. d4 { has been played at the highest level earlier. } 7... Qe7 8. Be2 O-O 9. Nf3 exd4 10. exd4 Re8 11. h3 b6 12. cxb6 (12. Be3 bxc5) 12... axb6 13. Be3 Ne4 { seemed fine for black in Rustemov - Sokolov, 2001. } (13... Ra3 { might have been even better. Threatening a very dangerous exchange sacrifice on e3. } 14. O-O (14. Qc1 Ne4 { Nxf2 is now a threat. } 15. O-O Rc3 16. Qb2 Ng3 17. Rfe1 Rxe3 18. fxe3 Qxe3+ { is a silly engine line. Black is obviously much better here. }) 14... Rxe3!)) 7... Nc6 8. Be2 O-O (8... e4 { looks like a critical test to 7.Nf3. } 9. Nd4 Nxd4 (9... O-O 10. Bb2 b6 11. Nxc6 dxc6 12. cxb6 axb6 13. O-O Qd6 { Blacks position looks decent. In the future he can start putting pressure on the c4 pawn with moves like Be6 Qc5 and Nd7-e5. However, white has a nice bishop pair. }) 10. exd4 { whites doubled pawns dominate the center. He also has the bishop pair. It is obvious that he must be better. } 10... O-O 11. O-O d5 12. cxd6 Qxd6 13. Bb2) 9. Bb2 d6 10. cxd6 cxd6 11. O-O Re8 12. a4 b6 13. d3 (13. d4 { also looks natural, but it might make blacks task a bit easier. } 13... Bb7 14. d5 Na5 { black can start putting pressure on the c4-pawn. White does not want to close the position like this with a bishop pair against a pair of horses. }) 13... Bg4 { it is hard to decide where to put blacks light squared bishop. In a perfect world you would probably want it on b7 in the long a8-h1 diagonal. But it's not clear what it would be doing there after moves like e4, or d4-d5. On g4 it plans to swap itself on e2. If white wants to move his knight while keeping his bishop pair he is forced to play moves like h3 and g4 which might weaken his kingside. } 14. h3 Bh5 15. g4 Bg6 16. Nh4 Rc8 17. Nxg6 hxg6 { White now has a full bishop pair to blacks pair of knights. In general white would now want to open the position. However, his king is slightly exposed, making opening up the position risky. } 18. Bf3 { A very natural move. Now both bishops are in the longest diagonals on the board. At the same time it eyes the important d5 and e4 square. } 18... g5 { Blacks tries to stop ideas like h4 and f4, while at the same time prepareing to bring his knight on c6 to the kingside with Ne7 and Ng6. } (18... Nd7 { bringing the knight to c5 also looks natural but after } 19. Bg2 Nc5 20. d4 { it has to go back again, as Ne6 would run into the nasty d5. } 20... Ne6 (20... Nd7 { White is probably better here due to his space advantage and bishop pair. But it is not clear how he will proceed. At the same time the pawn on c4 might become a target, after the pawn moves away from d3. } 21. Qd3 Na5 22. Rac1 Qc7 { [%csl Gc4] } 23. Rc2 { is a very complicated middlegame. }) 21. d5) 19. Bg2 Nd7 (19... Ne7 { is another logical plan. Black wants to bring his knight to g6 to stop f4 and h4. But it also allows white to break on the queenside. } 20. a5! bxa5 (20... Ng6 21. axb6 Qxb6 22. Qd2 Rb8 23. Bc3 { again white must be better. The pawn on a7 is a target and the white bishop pair is very strong. It is also not clear what the black knights are doing. }) 21. Qa4 { white must be better. He will regain his pawn and put pressure in the open a and b-fiiles. }) 20. f4! { Giri decides that its time to break in the centre. } 20... gxf4 21. exf4 Nc5 (21... exf4 22. Rxf4 { White is much better. He can start stacking pieces in the f-file. The bishops on b2 and g2 are monsters. }) 22. fxe5 dxe5 23. Bd5! { Strong attacking chess. White improves his bishop and eyes f7. } 23... Rf8 (23... Rc7 24. Qf3 { looks crushing } { [%csl Gf7,Gc6] } 24... Qf6 25. Qg3 Qg6 26. Rf5 { [%csl Ge5,Gf7][%cal Ga1f1] }) 24. Qf3! { Attacks both c6 and f7. It is clear that something has gone terribly wrong for black. White's pieces are much better and he can proceed however he wants. F.ex. with Rf2 followed with Rf1, or Rae1 to put pressure on e5. At the same time black has to find a way to defend all his pieces. } 24... Qd7 25. Bc3 { Simple chess. White is simply improving all his pieces. On c3 the bishop prepares the a5-break. Black has no easy way to improve his position. } 25... Ne6 { black hopes to put a fat knight on d4. However, the pawn on a4 is no longer attack allowing white to improve his rook on a1. } 26. Rae1 { Improves the rook and put pressure on the e5-pawn. White has no easy way to protect the pawn, as f6 would run into a deadly attack } 26... Ne7 (26... f6 27. Qf5 Rce8 28. d4! { a crushing blow. Black will lose material when the e-file opens. } (28. Be4 { also looks tempting }) 28... exd4 (28... Nxd4 29. Bxd4 exd4 30. Rxe6 $18) (28... Kh8 29. dxe5 Nxe5 30. Bxe5 fxe5 31. Qh5+ Kg8 32. Qxe5 $18 { is resignable }) 29. Rxe6 $18) 27. Rxe5 Nxd5 28. Rxd5 { White now has a full pawn and much better pieces. The position must be winning. } 28... Qxa4 { Anand tries to regain his material, but now his queen is a long way from the action on the kingside. } 29. g5? { Giri doesn't find the cleanest way to finish the game. But his position is still superior. The bishop on c3 is a monster. Black's king is very exposed, and his pieces are passive. } (29. Rh5!! { looks very tempting. White now threatens Qe4 or Qf5 with mating ideas. } 29... Rc5 { black has to try to get rid of the rook on h4 to survive. } (29... a6 30. Qf5 g6 31. Rh8#) 30. Be5! { renews the threat of Qe4. Black has nothing better than to give up the exchange. } 30... Rxe5 31. Rxe5 { white must be winning. }) 29... Rc5 { black hopes to exchange off white's strong rook on d5. } 30. h4 { Giri doesn't care about the rook exchange and decides to start pushing Harry. A pawn on h6 combined with the bishop on c3 would be deadly. } 30... Rxd5 31. cxd5 Nc5? { Anand has been under heavy pressure the entire game and makes a game ending mistake. But his position was close to hopless. } (31... Qxh4 { would have been a better try. The resulting endgames might give black some drawing chances. } 32. dxe6 Qxg5+ 33. Kh2 Qh6+ 34. Kg2 Qxe6 (34... Qg6+ 35. Qg3 { [%cal Gg3g7] } 35... Qxg3+ 36. Kxg3 fxe6 { the endgame is probably just winning for white. }) 35. Re1 Qd7 (35... Qg6+ 36. Kf2 { [%csl Gg7][%cal Ge1g1] } 36... Rd8 37. Rg1) 36. Bxg7 Kxg7 37. Qg3+ Kf6 38. Re4 { a silent killer. There is no defense against Qh4 } 38... Re8 39. Qh4+ Kg6 40. Rg4+ $18) 32. g6!! Qd7 (32... f5 33. Qh5 Qg4+ 34. Qxg4 fxg4 35. Re1 { The threat of Re7 decides the game. White will have two strong passed pawns in the g6 and h5 pawns. } { [%cal Ge1e7] }) 33. Bb4 { 1 - 0 } { d4 is coming. Black is losing heavy material and has no way to stop white's attack. } *


[Event "Norway Chess 2017: Caruana - Kramnik"]
[Date "2017.06.10"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C65"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Anti-Berlin Variation"]
[StudyName "Norway Chess 2017"]
[ChapterName "Caruana - Kramnik"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/HwXovdRZ/LbqNnMJc"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/lovlas"]
[UTCDate "2017.06.10"]
[UTCTime "09:38:56"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 { Kramnik is the one who introduced the Berlin defense to the highest level. He has had great results with it for over a decade. } 4. d3 { has become the modern approach to dealing with this system. } (4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 { is the berlin endgame. Many has tried and failed to get an edge with white in these lines. }) 4... Bc5 5. c3 (5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nxe5 { doesn't really work. } 6... Qd4! $19 { [%csl Gf2,Ge5] }) 5... d5 { A rare and very interesting move. } (5... O-O 6. O-O d6 { has historically been the main line. }) 6. exd5 (6. Nxe5 O-O 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. d4 Bb6 9. O-O dxe4 (9... Nxe4 10. Nxc6 Qf6 11. Nb4 Be6 12. Be3 (12. Nd2 c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Nd5 Qe5 16. Be3 Bxe3 { was seen in So - Caruana, 2016. Black is probably fine here. But white's majority on the Queenside can be difficult to deal with. }) 12... Qg6 13. Nd3) 10. Bg5 c5 11. Nd2 cxd4? (11... Bb7 { was probably better } 12. Ng4 cxd4 13. Nxf6+ gxf6 14. Bh6 f5 15. Bxf8 Qxf8 { black's pawn centre and bishop pair gives him enough compensation. }) 12. Nxe4 { gave white an advantage in Wei Yi - Karjakin, 2017. }) (6. Nbd2 dxe4 7. dxe4 O-O 8. O-O Qe7 9. Qe2 a5 10. Nh4 Bg4 { proved fine for black in Vachier-Lagrave - Giri, 2014. }) 6... Qxd5 7. Bc4 (7. O-O? { runs into problems } 7... Bxf2+ 8. Rxf2 Qxb5 $17 { black is a clear pawn up }) 7... Qd6 8. Qe2 O-O 9. Bg5 (9. Nbd2 a5 10. Ng5 { was played in both Topalov - Aronia, 2016, and Svidler - Inarkiev, 2016. }) 9... Be6 10. Nbd2 Bxc4 11. Nxc4 Qe6 12. Bxf6 gxf6 (12... Qxf6 { looks more normal. Maybe Kramnik was worried that his pawn on e5 would become exposed. }) 13. Nfd2 b5 14. Ne3 f5 15. a4 f4 16. Qg4+ Qg6 17. Qxg6+ hxg6 18. Nd5 Rad8 19. Nf6+ Kg7 20. Nfe4 Bb6 21. axb5 Ne7 22. Ke2 Nd5 23. g3 f5 24. Ng5 Rfe8 25. Nc4 e4 26. d4 f3+ 27. Kd2 Nf6 28. Ne3 Rd7 29. h4 Kh6 30. Rhd1 Nd5 31. Ra4 Kh5 32. Nh3 Nxe3 33. Kxe3 Kg4 34. Nf4 Rd6 35. Rc4 Re5 36. Rb4 Re8 37. Ra1 Re5 38. Ra6 Re8 39. Raa4 Rh8 40. Ra1 Re8 41. Ra3 Rh8 42. Rba4 a5 43. Ra1 c5 44. bxc6 Rxc6 45. Rxa5 Bxa5 46. Rxa5 g5 47. hxg5 Rh1 48. d5 Rc8 49. g6 Re1+ 50. Kd2 Rf1 51. Ke3 Re1+ 52. Kd2 Rf1 53. Ke3 { 1/2 -1/2 } *


