1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. a4 a5 { Thhis is quite rare. Usually black wants to have the pawn on a6. a5 stops c3 followed by b4. But it leaves a square on b5 white might get to use. It could also become a weakness in the endgame. } 7. Bg5 (7. c3 d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Re1 Bg4 10. Nbd2 { was played in Vachier-Lagrave - Aronian, 2016. }) 7... h6 8. Bh4 Be7 { A typical maneuver. If black did not play d6 yet, he can break the pin with Be7. } (8... g5 { is also a typical move in these lines. It's always hard to know whether g5 will leave blacks kingside too exposed. } 9. Bg3 d6) 9. Bg3 d6 10. h3 Kh8 { Aronian decides to go for a very interesting idea with an early f5. } 11. c3 Nh7 12. Qb3 f5 { Black opens the f-file and prepares to launch an attack on the kingside. } 13. exf5 Bf6 { prepares to take the pawn on f5 with the knight on c6. } (13... Bxf5 { was probably also perfectly playable. } 14. Nbd2 (14. Qxb7 Bd7 15. Qb3 Rxf3 16. gxf3 Bxh3 17. Re1 Rb8 18. Qc2 Bh4 { looks dangerous for white }) 14... Rb8) 14. Be6 Ne7 15. Nh4 Qe8 { Aronian brings his queen to the kingside. } 16. Bxc8 Rxc8 17. Ng6+ Nxg6 18. fxg6 Qxg6 19. Qxb7 Ng5 (19... Qxd3 20. Qb5 Qg6 21. Qxa5 { if white is able to defend he will have a dangerous passed pawn. }) 20. h4 Ne6 21. Qe4 Qh5 22. Nd2 Nf4 23. Bxf4 exf4 24. Qf3 (24. Qxf4 Bg5 { picks up material. }) 24... Qxh4 25. Rfe1 Rb8 { Simple chess. Aronian simply puts his rook on a better square. From b8 it hits the b2 pawn and controls a half open file. } 26. Nc4 g5! 27. Re6 Bg7 28. Rg6 Rbe8 { Again Aronian finds a better spot for his rook. This time it covers the entire e-file. } 29. d4 Kh7 30. Qd3 Kg8 { white cannot stop f3 anymore } 31. d5 f3 32. gxf3 Rf4 33. Kg2 Ref8 34. Nd2 g4! { The final breakthrough. } 35. Kg1 R8f5 36. Ne4 Rxf3 37. Qd4 Re5 38. Ng3 Rxg3+ 39. fxg3 Qxg3+ 40. Kf1 Kh7 41. Rxg7+ Kxg7 { 0 - 1 } { Black will simply start pushing his g-pawn and remove his king from the pin. Mate is unavoidable. } *


