{ The game we all had been waiting for. The world champion against the blitz world champion. The title defender vs. the challenger. }
1. d4 (1. f4) 1... f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 { Carlsen scored 2/2 with the Stonewall Dutch in the blitz tournament. } 4. c4 d5 { The Stonewall used to be very popular. For some reason it has fallen out of fashion, but there is no doubt that the line leads to very interesting play. } 5. Nd2 Bd6 6. Nh3 O-O 7. O-O Nc6 { Most people would play 7...c6 and venture into familiar Stonewall territory. But we all know that Magnus isn't most people. From here the knight attacks the d4 pawn and controls the important e5 square. Black will usually be fine if he finds a way to play e5. } 8. e3 b6 9. b3 { White is generally a bit better in these structures. Black bishop on c8 has problems finding a decent square. At the same time white can simply develop his pieces and start putting pressure in the c-file. } 9... a5 { A sharp choice. Black now has the option to annoy the pawn on b3 with a4 at a later stage. As it turns out the a4 idea will be crucial. } 10. Bb2 Ba6 11. Nf4 Bxf4 12. exf4 { White has now taken control over the e5 square forever. But it comes at a price. The f-pawns have been doubled. } 12... Ne4 13. Re1 Re8 14. Re3 (14. Nxe4 fxe4 15. f3 dxc4 16. fxe4 { Looks like a cleaner way for white to keep his pressure in the centre }) 14... Qd7 15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. f3 dxc4 17. fxe4 cxb3 18. d5 { Whites problem is that the simple logical move axb3 runs into Rad8 with heavy pressure on the d4 pawn } (18. axb3 Rad8 19. Rc1 Re7 { Keeps eye on the c7 pawn. Black now threatens to take on d4. }) 18... exd5 19. Qxb3 a4! { This forces the Queen away from the a2-g8 diagonal thus allowing the d-pawn to advance } 20. Qxa4 Bf1! { Another beautiful and instructional move. Black exchanges his poor bishop and gets rid of an defender of e4. } 21. Qd1 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Na5 23. Rc3 { This move looks a bit strange. The idea was probably to avoid Nc4. But it runs into a beautiful display of power play } (23. Re1 { Would have been a better try but its clear that black has the initiative. } 23... Nc4 24. Bc3 Ra3) 23... d4! 24. e5 Nc4!! { What a beautiful move. From here the Knight threatens to jump to e3 and the bishop on b2. It cannot be taken due to Qd5. } 25. Rf3 { If we compare black and whites pieces its obvious that black must be much better, if not winning. } (25. Rxc4 Qd5+ { [%cal Gd5g2,Gd5c4] }) 25... c5 { Suddenly the bishop on b2 is made worthless by blacks strong pawn structure. } (25... Nxb2 26. Qb3+ { [%cal Gb3b2,Gb3g8] }) 26. Bc1 Qd5 27. Kh3 Rad8 28. Rd3 Re6 { Heeeere comes the rook lift. Whites king is suddenly under heavy fire } 29. Qf3 { Black threats of Rh6 proves too much for white to handle. Qf3 allows whites king to escape to g2. However, after the simple Qxf3 the d-pawn starts rolling. } 29... Qxf3 30. Rxf3 d3 { There is no good way to stop the d-pawn without losing decisive material. } 31. Be3 d2 32. Rd1 Rd3 { White cannot defend his bishop on e3. } 33. f5 Rxe5 { 0-1 White resigns. } { A beautiful and decisive game by the current world champion. } 0-1


