{ Best game of the simul goes to @doughrow for his crushing win. This game is a good example of how you should play to win without giving your opponent any counter chances. }
1. Nf3 { 1.Nf3 is a very flexible move. White can depending on blacks setup chose to transpose into either e4, d4 or c4 lines. I am a big fan of this move order. } 1... c5 { I decided to play englishish. Here white has several choices. He can transpose into a sicilian with 1.e4. Play 1.c4 an enter an English opening. Or he can play g3 and await future development. } 2. g3 d6 { I am not a big fan of this move. Better would probably be 2...Nc6 or 2...g6. } 3. Bg2 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nf6 (6... Qb6 { is the main line here, forcing white to devide where to put his knight. } 7. Be3 Qxb2 { This line can lead to very interesting play. Black has a pawn but white is able to finish his development without isseues. } 8. Nd2! Bxd4 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. Nc4 Qa6 11. Qxd4 $18 { Whites position is crushing. } { [%cal Gd4h8,Gg2a8,Ge3a7,Gb1b8] }) 7. c4 { We can already here see that black has problems finishing his development. Nc6 cant be played, as the bishop on g2 and the knight on d4 is protecting the c6 square. Bd7 hangs the b7 pawn. Meanwhile white can finish his development with easy by Nc3 and Bg6/f4/e3. } 7... O-O 8. Nc3 a6 { I have played this position several times online as black. I hate my life everytime. The idea behind a6 is to play Qc7 (without white responding Nb5) followed by Nc6. However a6 leaves the b6 square weak. One day white might play either b4-c5 or Be3 Na4, or even Nd5. Its hard to see how black is gonna equalize. } 9. b3 { Simple chess. White protects his c4 pawn and can now put his bishop on the long a1-h8 diagonal. } 9... Qc7 10. Bb2 Nc6 11. Rc1 { Strong play by white. As long as the black queen is on c7, black need to be aware of Nd5 and c5 ideas. } { [%cal Gc1c7] } 11... Bd7 (11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Be6 { Has been played in a few OTB games. There is no doubt that white has a better positions. He has space advantage and full control over the d5 square. One day white can aim to break with c5 or maybe even play e4, f4 and e5. Black needs to tread very carefully. }) 12. Nc2 { White again finds a strong plan. Nc2 has the simple idea of playing Ne3-d5 in the near future. This secures that he will have a fat knight on the important d5 square. It also makes sure white get to keep more pieces on the board. Its important to note that as white has the space advantage he want to try to keep as many pieces as possible on the board. Meanwhile blacks pieces are cramped. } 12... Rfe8 { Protects the e7 pawn. Its very hard to find an active plan for black. So I was happy trying to improve my piece placement, hoping that white one day would make a mistake. } 13. e4 { This makes sure black can never ever ever play d5. In the near future white will play Ne3, move his queen, put a rook in the d-line and play something like Nd5 or b4-c5. He can also consider playing f4 with the idea to one day maybe play e5. This clearly shows how superior whites position is. He doesn't really need to do anything, he can just carefully improve his position. Black has no active good ideas. } 13... Rac8 14. Ne3 e6 { tries to regain control over the d5 square. However, this leaves the d6 pawn and the d-file exposed. } { [%csl Gd6] } 15. Qd2 Red8 16. Rfd1 { [%csl Gd6] } 16... Be8 { Here white had the very strong Ncd5 winning the game almost at once. But its hard to criticize whites play. His position is clearly superior and he should be in no rush to end things. Sometimes its better to be safe than sorry. So the engine can fuck off. } 17. Ba3 (17. Ncd5 exd5 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Nxd5 { and black can resign. } { [%csl Gf6,Gc7] }) 17... Bf8 18. Bb2 Bg7 19. Kh1! { On g1 the king might be exposed to Qb6 ideas after white plays f4. This move is a perfect exmaple of prophylaxis, where the player anticipates future problems and just avoids them all together before continuing his plan. Beautiful strategic play. } 19... Ne5 20. h3! { again a beautiful move. Why not just remove the g4 square from the knights forever? } 20... h5 21. f4 { If white did not play h3 black could now put a knight on g4 and try to exchange one pair of horses. If the king was on g1 black could maybe consider Qb6 followed by dxe5 and Bh6. Just look at how masterly white has avoided all the complications by simple means. } 21... Nc6 { again Ncd5 was a very strong option. With the same line as earlier. } 22. Qf2 (22. Ncd5! exd5 23. Bxf6 Bxf6 24. Nxd5 $18 { again black can resign. But white is in no hurry to end things. } { [%cal Gd5f6,Gd5c7] }) 22... Nb4 23. g4 { Imo white should maybe continue improving his piece placement before breaking. 23.a3 would force blacks knight back to c6. Afterwards white could consider playing b4, or even doubling his rook in the d-file. 23.g4 is certainly a strong move. But if white just continues improving his pieces it might be even stronger in the near future. } (23. a3 Nc6 24. b4 Qb8 25. g4) 23... hxg4 24. hxg4 e5? { Black is desperate for counterplay. I was hoping there maybe was some ideas with Bh6 and Qc5. But to be honest blacks position is hopeless. e5 leaves the bishop on g7 with almost no squares. At the same time it gives up the control of the d5 square. But what else is black supposed to do? } 25. f5 Qc5 26. Bf3?? { For some reason I didn't play this simple move. Finally white has made a mistake and allowed black to get some counterplay. Its very hard for black to defend the knight on e3, as Re1 runs into Nd3, with a family fork. } 26... Bc6?? (26... Bh6! { [%cal Gc5f2,Gh6c1] } 27. a3 Qxe3 28. Qxe3 Bxe3 29. axb4 b5! 30. Ra1 bxc4 31. Rxa6 Bd4 { Suddenly all white pawns are weak and blacks pieces are strongly positioned. Even the bishop on e8 has a future on c6. }) 27. g5! { Bam. Blacks pieces are running out of squares. } 27... Nh7 28. f6 Bf8 { Just look at the knight on h7 and the bishop on f8. They are destined to burn forever on h7 and f8 as they have no squares. } 29. Qg1 { Another nice prophylactic move. On f2 the queen is undefended. On g1 she is hanging out with her friends the king and the rooks. She also keeps the hardworking g5 pawn under control. } 29... Bd7 { Black is running out of moves. His position is hopeless. But maybe he could have tried Nxf6 followed by gxf6 and Bh6. At least then his black squared bishop is active. } 30. Ba3 { [%cal Ga3c5] } 30... a5 31. Rd2 { White has the simple idea of putting his heavy pieces in the h-line. Mate is imminent. } 31... Be6 32. Ncd5 Bxd5 33. Rxd5 Qa7 34. Bxb4 axb4 35. Rc2 Rc5 36. Rdd2 b5 37. Rh2 bxc4 38. Nxc4 Rc7 39. Qg3 Bg7 40. Rxh7! Kxh7 41. Qh4+ Kg8 42. fxg7 Kxg7 43. Qh6+! Kg8 44. Rh2 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Mate follows. White has a played an almost perfect game by simply avoiding all counterplay and carefully improving his position. } 1-0


