1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 { Don't do this at home kids. 3.exd5 is not the move of great warriors. } 4. Nf3 Nc6 { In the recent years I have become quite fond of the 4...Nc6 lines. Black can usually continue with the setup: Bd6 Nge7 Bf5 Qd7 and enjoy complete equality. } 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bg5 Nf6 { This is a stupid stupid stupid move by me. Nge7 is a much easier continuation. } (6... Nge7 7. Bd3 Be6 8. O-O Qd7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Qc2 h6 11. Bh4 Bf5 { Black can't be worse here. }) 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O h6 9. Bh4 Re8 10. Nbd2 g5 { Since black was foolish enough to put his knight on f6 he has to play either g5 or Be7 to break the knight pin. I was feeling frisky and decided to go for the shaper approach. } 11. Nxg5 { Oh man. White is also feeling frisky. This is a sac you will find in many similar positions. Black can usually consolidate with hxg5 Kg7 and continue his development. However, in this position white might get sufficient compensation as his pieces are already developed. White can continue with plans like f4-f5, Qf3 and then try to take control over the e-line. } 11... hxg5 12. Bxg5 Kg7 (12... Be7 { Might have been a safer approach. But its hard to see where black will put his king after something like Qf3->g3 threatening at least perpetual. Great warriors don't want to allow perpetual. }) 13. f4 Rh8 (13... Re3 { Is another interesting possibility. On e3 the black rook stops the Qf3 idea. It also forces white to exchange a pair of rooks if he wants to try to swing his rook on f3 to h3/g3. }) 14. Qf3 Ne7 { Black need to bring his pieces into the defence. Black is now threatening to play Bf5, trying to exchange of whites strong light squared bishop. } 15. Bxf6+ { I think white is better off if he keeps his bishop on the board. On g5 it is super annoying and could in the future create chaos. Blacks king might seem exposed to f6 but he can easily bring his queen to g8 and follow with Bf5 and Re8. Black seems to be fine. } 15... Kxf6 16. Qg3 Qg8 17. Qg5+ Qxg5 { After the queen exchange black is up a piece for two pawns. Thats a lot. } 18. fxg5+ Kg7 19. Nf3 Bg4 20. h3 Be6 21. Rae1 Rae8 22. Ne5 c5 23. Rf6 Rh5?? { I overlooked whites strong reply. Much better would have been. } (23... Bxe5 24. Rxe5 cxd4 25. cxd4 Rh4 { and white loses material, as g4 drops the h3 pawn. Blacks king is perfectly safe guarded by his good friends. } { [%cal Gh4d4] }) 24. Nxf7! Bxf7 25. Rxd6 cxd4 26. Rd7 Kf8 27. g6 (27. Rxb7! Rxg5 28. Bb5 { and black loses material as he cannot save both his rook on e8 and knight on e7. }) 27... Bxg6 28. Rf1+ Kg8 29. Rxe7 Rxe7 30. Bxg6 Rhe5 31. cxd4 Re2 32. Rf2 Re1+ 33. Kh2 Kg7 34. Bh5 Kh6 35. Bf3 Rd7 36. Rd2 a5 37. Rc2 Kg5 38. Rc5 Kf4 39. Rxa5 Ke3 40. Rxd5 Rxd5 41. Bxd5 b6 42. g4 Re2+ 43. Kg3 Rxb2 44. g5 Rb5 45. Be6 Rxg5+ 46. Kh4 Kf4 47. d5 b5 48. Bf7 Rg7 49. Be8 Rh7+ 50. Bh5 Rh6 $22 { Zugzwang } 51. a3 Kf5 52. d6 Rxd6 53. Kg3 Rd3+ 54. Kf2 Rxh3 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


