1. d4 f5 2. Bg5 d5?! { Here's a look at the alternatives: } (2... Nf6?! 3. Bxf6 exf6 4. e3 d5 { transposes to the game; }) (2... h6 3. Bh4 g5 4. e3 Nf6 5. Bg3 d6 6. h4 { Diagram [#] } 6... g4 (6... Rg8 7. hxg5 hxg5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Qd2 Qe7 10. O-O-O Nc6 11. f3 Bd7 12. e4 { White's development, pawn center, and control of the
open file give him a clear advantage }) 7. h5 Bg7 8. Nc3 c6 9. Bd3 Qa5 10. Ne2 O-O 11. Nf4 e5 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Bc4+ Kh7 14. Ne6 { and White wins the bishop
pair cleanly; }) (2... c6 { (this is probably the best alternative to 2 ... g6.
The main idea is to attack the undefended b-pawn by ... Qb6, or to play a
Stonewall if White defends against that. I don 't like the Dutch Defense,
especially on move 1, but if I had to play it I would probably choose 2 ... c6
here) } 3. Nd2 { (I like this move because 3.Nc3 makes the Stonewall 3 ... d5
look decent, while 3.Nf3 takes away the check on h5 (after e2-e3) , making 3. .
.h6 playable) } 3... Qb6 (3... d5 4. e3 Qb6 5. Ngf3 (5. Rb1) 5... Qxb2 6. Rb1) 4. e3! { (of course White can defend in various ways, but then the Stonewall is
much better than in the note to move 3) } 4... Qxb2 5. Bd3 d5 6. Ne2 g6 { Diagram [#] } 7. c4! $146 { (the 'rule of thumb' is that if you get 3 tempi for a pawn,
that's a good deaL It's hard to count tempi here, but I think White has at
least the needed three, as the black queen is a liability) } 7... Qa3 (7... Bg7) 8. Nf4 e6 (8... h6 9. Nxg6 Qxd3) 9. h4 (9. Rb1) 9... Nh6 10. Rb1 Bg7 11. Rb3 (11. Qb3) 11... Qf8 (11... Qd6 12. Nh5 Qf8 13. Nxg7+ Qxg7 14. Qb1 Nd7 (14... b6 15. cxd5 cxd5) 15. Rxb7 Bxb7 16. Qxb7 Rb8 17. Qxc6 O-O) 12. O-O { White has
tremendous compensation for the pawn in terms of development, space, and king
safety, but no clear winning plan. He has ideas like h4-h5 and/or f2-f3. } 12... Nf7 13. Rxb7 Bxb7 (13... Nxg5 14. Qb1 Nd7 15. hxg5 Qe7 16. cxd5 exd5 17. Rb3) 14. Nxe6 Qd6 (14... Qg8 15. Bf4 Nd7 16. Qb3 Nb6 17. c5 Kd7 18. cxb6 (18. Nc7 Rc8 (18... Bh6) 19. cxb6 a6 20. Nc4 dxc4 21. Bxc4 Qf8 22. Ne6)) 15. Nxg7+ Kf8 16. Qb3 Bc8 (16... Qd7) (16... Ba6 17. Bf4 Qd7 18. Nxf5 gxf5 19. Bxb8 dxc4 20. Nxc4)) 3. e3 Nf6 (3... c6 4. c4 Qb6 { (Black needs to move the queen to permit ...
e7-e6, but in the Stonewall the queen normally goes to the kingside. White's
bishop on g5 makes the Stonewall ineffective) } 5. Qc2 e6 6. Nc3 Nd7 7. Bd3 Ngf6 8. Nge2 Ne4 9. Bxe4 fxe4 10. Nf4 Nf6 11. O-O Be7 12. f3 exf3 13. Rxf3 { White
has much better development and kingside attacking prospects. Black's bishop
pair is useless here. }) 4. Bxf6 exf6 5. c4 { Diagram [#] } 5... Bb4+ { If Black has to
surrender this bishop for a knight his opening is garbage, but otherwise the
pressure on d5 is a problem: } (5... Be6 6. Nc3 dxc4 7. d5 Bf7 8. Bxc4 Bd6 9. Nge2 O-O 10. Nd4 Qd7?! (10... g6?! 11. h4 Qe7 12. h5 Nd7 13. Ne6 Rfe8 14. hxg6 hxg6 15. Qd4 { and White has a winning attack; }) (10... Qc8 { (relatively
best) } 11. O-O Nc6 12. dxc6 Bxc4 13. Qf3 bxc6 14. Rfd1 Qd7 15. Rac1 { and White
will regain his pawn with much better pawn structure and development. It is
unlikely that Black will retain the bishop pair for long }) 11. Qf3 g6 12. Ne6 $146 Re8 13. g4 Qe7 14. gxf5 { White wins a pawn for free. }) 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Qb3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 dxc4 9. Bxc4+ Kh8 10. Ne2 { White has more center pawns, better
development, and better pawn structure, all for free. } 10... c5 { Diagram [#] } 11. h4 (11. O-O { with a clear advantage, but the text
looks even better. }) 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 g6 13. Nf4 Nc6 14. Rc1 { Diagram [#] } 14... Qd6? (14... Na5 { was necessary } 15. Qb4 Nxc4 16. Rxc4 Rf7 17. Qb3 Kg8 18. Rc3 Qd6 19. O-O { and White is obviously better as Black can only develop at the
price of a pawn. }) 15. h5 g5 16. Ng6+ hxg6 17. hxg6+ Kg7 18. Bf7 Rh8 19. Rxh8 Kxh8 20. Ke2 Qh2 21. Qb1 Kg7 22. Rh1 Qxg2 23. Rh7+ Kf8 24. Bc4 Ke8 25. g7 Ne7 26. Qb4 1-0


